    those who choose to defer or play down workforce participation to care\r\n\
    for their children.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The women\xE2\x80\x99s movement\xE2\x80\x99s support for Howard\xE2\x80\x99s proposal would only further\r\n\
    entrench these women\xE2\x80\x99s beliefs that feminists see little value in their\r\n\
    decision not to work, or to work part-time to be there when the school\r\n\
    bell rings at 3.30.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Limited resources (for example, the Howard Government recently de-funded\r\n\
    the Women\xE2\x80\x99s Electoral Lobby) is another reason the women\xE2\x80\x99s movement\r\n\
    would benefit from concentrating all its attention on traditional\r\n\
    feminist and unquestionably gender-based issues concerning women and\r\n\
    work - issues such as equal pay, sexual harassment and glass ceilings.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Ironically, such a concentration may also bring more women back into the\r\n\
    feminist fold because nearly all women believe - no matter how\r\n\
    stridently anti-feminist their rhetoric - that they have a right to as\r\n\
    much pay, as much safety and as much opportunity for advancement at work\r\n\
    as any man.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Bringing men into the fight for work/family balance better reflects the\r\n\
    reality and ideal of male involvement in parenting. More importantly,\r\n\
    until working fathers start kicking up a fuss - and threatening to down\r\n\
    tools, alongside working mothers - nothing is going to change.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    School hours are only the tip of the iceberg when it comes to the\r\n\
    problems facing working mothers and fathers. Working parents missed the\r\n\
    opportunity that Howard\xE2\x80\x99s comments offered to begin a discussion at the\r\n\
    community and political level about the degraded quality of life they\r\n\
    and their children have as a result of the incongruence between\r\n\
    institutions such as school and work, and the demands of parenthood. It\r\n\
    may be that we can no longer expect the women\xE2\x80\x99s movement to take up this\r\n\
    fight on our behalf.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Perhaps, if we use the time until the Government\xE2\x80\x99s next political\r\n\
    opening organising a new movement for change - I\xE2\x80\x99d call it Parents for\r\n\
    Balance - we won\xE2\x80\x99t have to see the next opportunity float by."
