    career also takes time, and leads women to delay even longer. Getting so\r\n\
    established at work that a woman is able to negotiate a family-friendly\r\n\
    work arrangement that won\xE2\x80\x99t bankrupt her, turn her hair grey or put her\r\n\
    on the mummy track could conceivably - in a time of unequal opportunity\r\n\
    and pay - take a lifetime.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The limited lifespan of female fertility means such delays may result in\r\n\
    a woman having fewer children than she intended, or no children at all.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The upshot of all this is that the incompatibility of child-bearing and\r\n\
    child-rearing with the demands of the lean and mean modern-day workforce\r\n\
    - and the aggravation of that incompatibility by sex discrimination - is\r\n\
    an issue that bears directly on the population question. No wonder\r\n\
    politicians are happy to restrict debates on population to questions of\r\n\
    immigration. Debates on the causes of declining fertility could make\r\n\
    arguments about migrant numbers look like fun.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But curtailment of this important debate comes at a high cost for\r\n\
    present and potential parents and children. So, as our political leaders\r\n\
    gear up for the annual carry-on about migrant numbers, prospective and\r\n\
    actual parents need to ensure their elected representatives canvass all\r\n\
    the causes and cures for our declining numbers.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The wellbeing of our families - and the existence of those we hope to\r\n\
    have - depends on it."
