    practices surrounding pregnancy may, by imposing alternative ethical\r\n\
    requirements on pregnant women, alienate them from their own intuitive\r\n\
    understanding of the range and limits of the moral obligations that\r\n\
    arise from the \xE2\x80\x9Cpregnant relationship:\xE2\x80\x9D the evolving relationship\r\n\
    between the pregnant woman and her fetus.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    During pregnancy a woman is becoming a mother, a process she completes\r\n\
    when the child is born. At the center of this becoming is her evolving\r\n\
    relationship with her fetus. For most women this relationship is\r\n\
    initially only known, not felt (\xE2\x80\x9CThe line in the box on the stick says I\r\n\
    am pregnant but I don\xE2\x80\x99t feel anything.\xE2\x80\x9D), but it comes to occupy the\r\n\
    center of her thoughts, dreams, hopes and body by the time the baby is\r\n\
    due. Most women increasingly come to love the fetus inside them as it\r\n\
    progressively makes its presence felt in her body and life. As time goes\r\n\
    on, they grow eager for the baby to emerge from their bodies, where they\r\n\
    will \xE2\x80\x9Cconsummate\xE2\x80\x9D the relationship begun in-utero, through sight, smell,\r\n\
    touch and nurture.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The existence and practice of antenatal screening imposes other ethical\r\n\
    imperatives on women, while the limitations of the screens may hinder\r\n\
    the normal development of the relationship between mother and fetus.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Ethicist Paul Laurtizen believes the mere existence of medical\r\n\
    technology can compel people to \xE2\x80\x9Cchoose\xE2\x80\x9D it. In other words, if a woman\r\n\
    does not choose to have a pre-natal screen and she gives birth to a\r\n\
