  title: "Book Review - \xE2\x80\x9CThe End of Equality: Work, Babies and Women\xE2\x80\x99s Choices in 21st Century Australia\xE2\x80\x9D"
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:34:22
  content_markup: "<p>By Anne Summers, Random House Australia, 2003. Paperback RRP $29.95</p>\n\n\
    <p>TEASE: Who better than Anne Summers, a woman who lists among her\n\
    achievements the best-selling book Damned Whores and God\xE2\x80\x99s Police,\n\
    advisor to former Prime Minister Keating and Officer of the Order of\n\
    Australia for services to journalism and women, to write about the most\n\
    pressing social problem of our time: the tragic imbalance between work\n\
    and family responsibilities, and the devastating impact it is having on\n\
    women\xE2\x80\x99s well-being and the nation\xE2\x80\x99s capacity to reproduce itself?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Heaven knows there has been no shortage of column inches dedicated to\n\
    the problem, as well as diligent hand-wringing and sympathetic clucking\n\
    noises from the Howard government. Yet while the problem seems to worsen\n\
    almost hourly, the Government does nothing. The reason for this, Summers\n\
    explains, is that the Government\xE2\x80\x99s ideological preference for\n\
    traditional family arrangements &ndash; where Daddy brings home the bacon and\n\
    Mum cares for house and kids &ndash; precludes it from implementing policies\n\
    designed to reduce working women\xE2\x80\x99s stress.</p>\n\n\
    <p>To the contrary, this bias leads the Government to blatantly\n\
    discriminate against families where both parents work by viciously\n\
    underfunding childcare, and implementing tax and benefit policies that\n\
    leave families with two earner $75 a week worse off on average than\n\
    those with only one. Summers argues that Australian women are often\n\
    unaware of such discriminatory policies because of the government\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    decision to either eliminate or enfeeble the agencies that in the past\n\
    not only would have publicly argued against them, bout kept ongoing tabs\n\
    on the impact they were having on women\xE2\x80\x99s equality.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Close to forty years on the political stage has done nothing to taint or\n\
    muffle Summers\xE2\x80\x99 activist indignation and thirsting for justice. She is\n\
    not afraid to name names in her expansive discussion of how both Labour\n\
    and Liberal politicians have failed women, as well as tossing bouquets\n\
    at the few men &ndash; Victorian QC Chris Maxwell comes in for special mention\n\
    &ndash; who use their power and influence to pursue justice for women. Given\n\
    that she was amongst the band of optimistic second-wave feminists who\n\
    confidently predicted that the mere presence of more women in Canberra\n\
    would make a difference, I particularly admired her willingness to\n\
    express disappointment in the 60 female members and senators who now\n\
    comprise over a quarter of pollies on the Federal benches for failing to\n\
    agitate on behalf of women. Emily\xE2\x80\x99s List (the Labour women\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    organization that funds progressive female candidates) rightly comes in\n\
    for particular scrutiny for its inability &ndash; despite requiring all the\n\
    candidates it funds to demonstrate that they are pro-choice and\n\
    pro-childcare &ndash; to \xE2\x80\x9Cgalvanise\xE2\x80\x9D women to act on these commitments once\n\
    elected.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Throughout the book, Summers reveals herself to be a woman who doesn\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    just get mad, but gets active. She writes unselfconsciously (as if\n\
    everyone leaps into constructive action when their fundamental values\n\
    are challenged) about her outrage at Prime Minister Howard\xE2\x80\x99s failure to\n\
    appoint a female Governor General, and his subsequent leaking to the\n\
    media that he desired to do so (leaving the clear impression that there\n\
    wasn\xE2\x80\x99t a single woman in the country who was qualified). Grabbing a copy\n\
    of Who\xE2\x80\x99s Who, it took Summers less than an hour to come up with 45 names\n\
    of women who were more than qualified for the post.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I must admit to being somewhat disappointed by the analysis Summers\n\
    provides of the causes of &ndash; and cures for &ndash; the work/family crunch and\n\
    resultant \xE2\x80\x9Cfertility strike.\xE2\x80\x9D Unlike her discussion of violence and the\n\
    subterranean but highly politically sophisticated way in which the\n\
    Howard government has \xE2\x80\x9Cdisappeared\xE2\x80\x9D women from the political agenda &ndash;\n\
    where she clearly knows her way well around the factual and conceptual\n\
    terrain &ndash; she consistently fails to call on the intellectual apparatus\n\
    needed to make sense of the varied and complex things women want, do and\n\
    settle for when it comes to work and family. There is no doubt this\n\
    areas is complicated, with seeming contradictions at every turn. What to\n\
    make, for instance, of repeated surveys that show that young Australian\n\
    women are as committed as young men to the paid workforce (to remaining\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cattached\xE2\x80\x9D to it and progressing up the career ladder), but others that\n\
    reveal substantial numbers of women claiming to \xE2\x80\x9Cchoose\xE2\x80\x9D total\n\
    withdrawal from the paid workforce or insecure part-time non-career\n\
    related jobs when they become mothers? \xE2\x80\x9CConstrained choice\xE2\x80\x9D and the\n\
    meaning of being a \xE2\x80\x9Cnon-chooser\xE2\x80\x9D in liberal democratic societies like\n\
    Australia are just some of the concepts found in thoughtful feminist\n\
    analysis of women\xE2\x80\x99s work/life decisions that would have assisted Summers\n\
    to both explain such trends, and point the way ahead.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But if you\xE2\x80\x99ve got a pulse and care about justice for women, you\xE2\x80\x99re sure\n\
    to finish the book itching to do something &ndash; anything &ndash; to catapult\n\
    women\xE2\x80\x99s quest for equality back on to the national agenda. Wisely,\n\
    Summers is prepared, dedicating her final chapter to a list of \xE2\x80\x9Cten ways\n\
    to change the world\xE2\x80\x9D and a directory of the relevant organizations and\n\
    individuals to contact to make your displeasure known. Since going to\n\
    press, she has even put this information up on her new website\n\
    (annesummers.com.au) where &ndash; with the aid of hyperlinks &ndash; it is even\n\
    easier to get started.</p>\n\n\
    <p>\xE2\x80\x9CDon\xE2\x80\x99t get mad,\xE2\x80\x9D Summers advises, \xE2\x80\x9Cget justice.\xE2\x80\x9D The rest she knows, is\n\
    up to us.</p>\n"
