    disagree with her assertion that the reason the movement has shied away\r\n\
    in the past is the \xE2\x80\x9Crepulsiveness\xE2\x80\x9D of foetal remains.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    No, the real problem with focusing on the fetus is that it leaves women\r\n\
    - literally - out of the picture. A typical fetal image is of a\r\n\
    balled-up cosmonaut in a circular, disembodied capsule. It is rare for\r\n\
    the line surrounding the fetus to even gesture at its reality as a\r\n\
    woman\xE2\x80\x99s womb, or to the geographical relationship of the capsule to the\r\n\
    rest of the woman\xE2\x80\x99s body (is she sitting or standing? In which direction\r\n\
    are her feet and face?)\r\n\
    \r\n\
    More importantly than her body, a focus on the fetus leaves the woman\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    life out of the picture: her partnership status; her ability to parent\r\n\
    well; her plans and ambitions for the future. Yet it precisely this\r\n\
    context, and the way the woman approaches and makes her decision, that\r\n\
    makes her choice comprehensible, and provides its moral texture and\r\n\
    meaning.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The anti-choice movement knows this. That is why the \xE2\x80\x9Chard cases\xE2\x80\x9D -\r\n\
    unwanted pregnancies resulting from incest and rape, or those that\r\n\
    threaten a woman\xE2\x80\x99s life - split the movement in two. Because while such\r\n\
    foetuses are as alive and human as any other, most refuse to condemn\r\n\
    women who abort in such circumstances. Better than any other, these\r\n\
    cases show it is our judgements about women\xE2\x80\x99s motives and intentions\r\n\
    that determine our moral evaluation of her particular abortion. And\r\n\
    experience shows such judgements to be harsher for strangers, and kinder\r\n\
    for friends. Abortion clinic staff repeatedly report doing terminations\r\n\
    for anti-choice protesters, only to find them - weeks later - on the\r\n\
    picket lines again.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    As Black\xE2\x80\x99s film testifies, feeling bad about abortion (or, more\r\n\
    precisely, feeling bad about finding oneself in the position of having\r\n\
    to face the decision at all) is testament that our moral sensibilities\r\n\
    are finely tuned, not that abortion is wrong. Most people who choose\r\n\
    divorce, particularly those with children, feel less than exultant about\r\n\
    having to make that decision; yet few believe this proves the choice was\r\n\
    wrong, or should be legally denied.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Black rarely spoke of her long-ago abortion. Few of the one in three\r\n\
    women who will have an abortion in their lifetime do. She says she wants\r\n\
    her film to change that, and the laws that in both the UK and many\r\n\
    states in Australia that hand doctors ultimate control over whether a\r\n\
    woman can get an abortion; requiring women \xE2\x80\x9Cto plead insanity to end an\r\n\
    unwanted pregnancy.\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The truth is no one knows what the reaction of the Australian public\r\n\
    will be to the film. But there is no reason why, if Black has done her\r\n\
    work well - ensuring both women and foetuses remain in the frame - than\r\n\
    supporters of abortion rights have anything to fear. It is a anti-choice\r\n\
    myth that women don\xE2\x80\x99t really know what they are doing when they\r\n\
    terminate, and that seeing foetal remains will reveal some previously\r\n\
    unrealised \xE2\x80\x9Ctruth\xE2\x80\x9D about the procedure.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The morality of abortion is, and will always be, far more complicated\r\n\
    than that."
