  title: Book Review - Night Thoughts in a Time of War - Bob Ellis
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:48:21
  content_markup: "<p>Night Thoughts in a Time of War by Bob Ellis, Viking, 2004.</p>\n\n\
    <p>TEASE: Most people are familiar with at least some of Bob Ellis\xE2\x80\x99s long\n\
    and impressive resume. The author of seventeen books, including the\n\
    bestselling Goodbye Jerusalem, Goodbye Babylon and First Abolish the\n\
    Customer, he\xE2\x80\x99s also written and directed features and documentaries\n\
    including The Notradamus Kid and Bastards from the Bush. He\xE2\x80\x99s won or\n\
    been nominated for numerous honours, including the Premier\xE2\x80\x99s Literary\n\
    Award.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Ellis is also a Labour speechwriter and quintessential leftie insider.\n\
    These days he works for Bob Carr, gets medical referrals from SA Premier\n\
    Mike Rann, and dines with Natasha (\xE2\x80\x9CTash\xE2\x80\x9D) Stott-Despoja and her\n\
    (extravagantly wanting, to Ellis\xE2\x80\x99s mind) fianc\xC3\xA9, Ian. He has regular\n\
    encounters with political big-wigs who impress him with their, \xE2\x80\x9Creason\n\
    and skill\xE2\x80\x9D (Kevin Rudd), the \xE2\x80\x9Csedate\xE2\x80\x9D manner in which they move\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Csecurely into history\xE2\x80\x9D (Whitlam and Graham Freudenberg) or their \xE2\x80\x9Crose\n\
    lips\xE2\x80\x9D and \xE2\x80\x9Cdreamy girlish beauty\xE2\x80\x9D (Maxine McKew and Stott-Despoja). In\n\
    return, they praise him for getting things \xE2\x80\x9Cas usual, dead right\xE2\x80\x9D (Susie\n\
    Annus), for being \xE2\x80\x9Cold-fashioned, but in a very, very nice way\xE2\x80\x9D (fellow\n\
    speechwriter Carol Green) and by laughing hysterically at his political\n\
    wit (Carr).</p>\n\n\
    <p>Some may find such windows into the personal relationships, intimate\n\
    thoughts and general comings and goings of contemporary power-brokers\n\
    offers welcome relief from the recycled press releases and 20-second\n\
    grabs that now substitutes for current affairs reporting in this\n\
    country. Others may see it as nothing more than name-dropping from an\n\
    aging man preoccupied with his own death and anxious about his own place\n\
    &ndash; and the place of the ideas he\xE2\x80\x99s championed all his life &ndash; in history.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Make no mistake about it, Ellis is a good guy. He feels for the needy\n\
    and is contemptuous of the greedy, and never fails to use his influence\n\
    to ease the suffering of the most forgotten and abused in Australian\n\
    society. He gave hospitality to Ali Bakhtiyari, the man whose sons fled\n\
    from detention but were refused refuge at the UK Consulate, and vainly\n\
    worked his contacts to prevent the children being shipped back to\n\
    Woomera.</p>\n\n\
    <p>There is also evidence, on numerous occasions, of a fine turn of phrase.\n\
    I love Ellis\xE2\x80\x99s description of taking his two dogs \xE2\x80\x9Cfor a whiffle on the\n\
    beach among the seaweed and the gulls and a town meeting of other\n\
    yelping dogs near the big tree\xE2\x80\x9D. With a few deft phrases, his\n\
    description of witnessing an IRA bombing in London back in the 1970s,\n\
    puts us right there.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Yet death confronts us on every page. Ellis admires his mother\xE2\x80\x99s fight\n\
    against her \xE2\x80\x9Cfinal descent\xE2\x80\x9D and rages against the dying of his own\n\
    personal light. He repeatedly laments the under-appreciation of the\n\
    contributions to politics and culture of dead white men he knew\n\
    personally or admired from history (does he fear a similar fate?), and\n\
    the denial of legitimacy to the varied excuses such men had for failing\n\
    to live up to expectations (as he fears he has?).</p>\n\n\
    <p>For those disinterested in this theme, the text offers little refuge.\n\
    While those who already share Ellis\xE2\x80\x99s world view may take comfort in his\n\
    passionate rehearsal of various left-wing lines (he\xE2\x80\x99s anti-Iraq war,\n\
    anti-Israel, anti-Bush, and pro asylum-seekers), those needing sustained\n\
    and logical argument to be persuaded of the wisdom of Ellis\xE2\x80\x99s assertions\n\
    will be disappointed. His attitude seems to be that you\xE2\x80\x99re either with\n\
    him or a\xE2\x80\x99gin him: if it\xE2\x80\x99s the former you need no persuasion, while those\n\
    in the latter camp will never be convinced, anyway. As a consequence,\n\
    what\xE2\x80\x99s on offer is never weightier than a moment-by-moment recounting of\n\
    recent events surrounding the war in Iraq, accompanied by Ellis\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    evaluation of whether any particular political action or attempt at spin\n\
    will \xE2\x80\x9Cplay\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Which leads me to my final reservation about Night Thoughts and all\n\
    books of it\xE2\x80\x99s genre (Noam Chomky\xE2\x80\x99s 9/11, Gore Vidal\xE2\x80\x99s Perpetual War for\n\
    Perpetual Peace): volumes that purport to offer a comprehensive analysis\n\
    of a recent event by \xE2\x80\x9Ca great thinker of our time\xE2\x80\x9D. If journalism is the\n\
    first draft of history, what exactly are such books? They claim to\n\
    provide more than the fact-reporting and superficial analysis\n\
    necessarily characteristic of writing forced to conform to the 24-hour\n\
    news cycle, yet starved of both distance from the event and the\n\
    perspective offered by time, their significance can be doubted. While\n\
    they are almost certainly catering to a book-buying market desperate to\n\
    make sense of our rapidly changing world, I remain sceptical &ndash; both in\n\
    theory and from experience- about their capacity to deliver.</p>\n\n\
    <p>A friend currently enjoying Night Thoughts says such criticism misses\n\
    the point. \xE2\x80\x9CEllis is not trying to say anything particularly new or\n\
    insightful. You read it because something big &ndash; like the war in Iraq &ndash;\n\
    happens and you think to yourself, \xE2\x80\x98Now I wonder what a bloke like Ellis\n\
    would think about that?\xE2\x80\x99\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n"
