    of the degrading and oppressive conditions women endured working in this\r\n\
    supposedly glamorous job appeared in Esquire in 1963, I was impressed\r\n\
    with her insights - published years later in a collection of essays -\r\n\
    into the cost of Bunnyhood not just to the minority of women who don\r\n\
    overlarge pink ears or pose for centrefolds, but to all women who live\r\n\
    in societies where Bunnyhood is seen as a suitable career aspiration for\r\n\
    young girls of talent.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This is what the Bunny logo means to me, and perhaps to other\r\n\
    feminist-minded women and men of my, and more mature, vintages. And this\r\n\
    is why I won\xE2\x80\x99t buy anything that carries it. But Bunny-stamped items are\r\n\
    selling well particularly - according to my local shop girl - to women\r\n\
    in their teens and early twenties. The question is: why?\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Perhaps the reason is simple, and actually suggests something quite\r\n\
    positive. The traditional Playboy model is far more rounded and\r\n\
    healthy-looking than the under-fed, under-slept female form idealised in\r\n\
    so many women\xE2\x80\x99s magazines. Maybe in wearing the Bunny symbol, what young\r\n\
    women are saying is that they are proud of their womanly curves, and\r\n\
    prefer them to looking like a heroin-addicted stick.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Another positive take on the Bunny\xE2\x80\x99s return is that in donning this\r\n\
    long-standing symbol of female oppression, women are reclaiming it as a\r\n\
    sign of empowerment. In the same way that Gays reclaimed as a symbol of\r\n\
    unity and pride the pink triangle that the Nazis used to brand and\r\n\
    oppress them, young Bunny-wearing women are boldly proclaiming their\r\n\
    faith in a world where Girl Power reigns and feminism - simply because\r\n\
    it is no longer needed - is a thing of the past. In such a world girls\r\n\
    can freely embrace both their femininity and sexuality without fear of -\r\n\
    as one Girl-Power scholar puts it - its \xE2\x80\x9Cusual worrisome baggage.\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    \r\n\
    A less optimistic interpretation, however, is that women\xE2\x80\x99s embrace of\r\n\
    the Bunny reflects their sense of disillusionment with - rather than\r\n\
    empowerment within - the post-industrial world in which they are coming\r\n\
    of age. Maybe, more than we realise, young women are tuning in when we\r\n\
    older ones complain of unequal wages, sexual harassment,\r\n\
    family-unfriendly policies and impenetrable glass ceilings at the\r\n\
    workplace. Perhaps they observe when those zealously guarding the reigns\r\n\
    of power either ridicule our distress, or ignore it. For such young\r\n\
    women, the Playboy symbol may hold out the time-honoured promise that if\r\n\
    they\xE2\x80\x99re pretty, \xE2\x80\x9Cput out\xE2\x80\x9D and otherwise play their cards right, there is\r\n\
    a way for them to make it to the top of the status and income pile: on\r\n\
    the arm of a wealthy and powerful man.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    So which interpretation is the correct one? The evidence, in my view, is\r\n\
    in favour of the Bunny as a symbol of Girl Power. Sure, there are\r\n\
    differences in the way the Gay Pride movement reclaimed the pink\r\n\
    triangle and the reappearance of the Bunny logo. The former was a\r\n\
    self-consciously political act by a grass-roots activist movement, while\r\n\
    the latter is nothing more than a marketing experiment. Nevertheless,\r\n\
    there are natty shorts with the Bunny on it and many more without -\r\n\
    ditto cute handbags - and significant numbers of young women are\r\n\
    choosing to buy the former. Given what we know about the optimism of\r\n\
    youth in general, and the disinterest of so many young women in a\r\n\
    feminism they see as irrelevant to their lives, there is good reason to\r\n\
    believe that in embracing the Bunny, young women see themselves as\r\n\
    reclaiming male-centred ideas of femininity and female sexuality, and\r\n\
    making them their own.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    It\xE2\x80\x99s hard not to admire them. Certainly, you can\xE2\x80\x99t blame them. Given the\r\n\
    choice of viewing the future in such a promising light or as hedged and\r\n\
    barricaded by entrenched, often subterranean but always fiercely\r\n\
    defended power and privilege, who wouldn\xE2\x80\x99t choose the former? And isn\xE2\x80\x99t\r\n\
    the belief that such a world can exist, indeed does exist, a necessary\r\n\
    prerequisite for actually bringing it about? \xE2\x80\x9CYou go girls,\xE2\x80\x9D I want to\r\n\
    cheer. And so I will.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    I just hope they\xE2\x80\x99re right."
