    At times, some of Australia\xE2\x80\x99s prominent civil libertarians sound like\r\n\
    fanatics - most recently when defending the rights of odious recidivist\r\n\
    sex offenders such as Victoria\xE2\x80\x99s Mr Baldy, due for release from prison\r\n\
    in August.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Mr Baldy was locked up for serial crimes of kidnapping and shaving the\r\n\
    heads of young boys before assaulting them. Soon after his first release\r\n\
    from jail, he attacked a young child again.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    I know it\xE2\x80\x99s the job of Liberty Victoria\xE2\x80\x99s vice-president, Jamie\r\n\
    Gardener, to condemn the intention of the Bracks Government to introduce\r\n\
    electronic tagging of repeat offenders like Mr Baldy. And I know it\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    his job to say things such as: \xE2\x80\x9CLiberty views with grave concern any\r\n\
    adding-on of sentences to people who have served their time set down by\r\n\
    the courts, (because this) is not something that is consistent with\r\n\
    human rights.\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But what folks like Mr Gardener often seem to forget is that no civil\r\n\
    right, no matter how important, is absolute. The rights of repeat sex\r\n\
    offenders like Mr Baldy need to be balanced against those of the\r\n\
    children to be protected from being his next victim.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Otherwise, when absolute rights clash, impenetrable deadlock is the\r\n\
    result, and all chance of consensus are lost.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The question is, does the Bracks plan get that balance right? I think it\r\n\
    does.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Mr Gardener\xE2\x80\x99s worry seems to be that tagging offenders punishes them\r\n\
    twice ~~- first by incarceration, then by monitoring~~- for the same\r\n\
    crime.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But this is not a continuing worry. If the tagging legislation passes,\r\n\
    future sentences will include post-release surveillance rather than\r\n\
    adding it on at the end.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This means that this problem - technically termed \xE2\x80\x9Cdouble jeopardy\xE2\x80\x9D -\r\n\
    falls away.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The real infringement of electronic surveillance is on a prisoner\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    rights to privacy. WHETHER the data from their bracelet is downloaded\r\n\
    daily through the phone or transmitted in real time, those wearing\r\n\
    electronic tags will be living in the Panopticon - an architectural\r\n\
    figure envisioned by political philosopher Jeremy Bentham.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    It has a central tower around which is built an annular structure\r\n\
    divided into cells that extend the entire width of the building to allow\r\n\
    both inner and outer windows.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The occupants of the cells are isolated from one another by walls, but\r\n\
    able to be observed collectively and individually by an unseen observer\r\n\
    in the tower.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The problem for the prisoners of the Panopticon is that they can be seen\r\n\
    - and know they can - but they are unable to see in return. They have no\r\n\
    idea of who is looking at them, when, and what - if anything - those\r\n\
    people plan to do with the knowledge they gain.0\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Even if data on their movements is not to be used against them\r\n\
    (something that is not the case with the electronic tag, which will most\r\n\
    likely be used to ensure prisoners conform to whatever movement\r\n\
    restrictions the courts sets down as a condition of their release),\r\n\
    those in the Panopticon suffer a complete loss of privacy and the\r\n\
    dignity and personal power that comes with it.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But if the electronic tags actually stop paedophiles from re-offending,\r\n\
    then this loss must be weighed against the gain of increased community\r\n\
    safety.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    According to Don Thomson, Professor of Forensic Psychology at Charles\r\n\
    Sturt University, we have reason to think that tagging will deter\r\n\
    offenders from committing further crimes against children. If the\r\n\
    prisoner knows an alarm will sound if he violates prescribed boundaries,\r\n\
    he\xE2\x80\x99s unlikely to do so on pain of either being caught in the act or, if\r\n\
    the violation is discovered only later, the certainty of being convicted\r\n\
    and locked away, perhaps for good.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    And there is some evidence from a handful of studies that electronic\r\n\
    monitoring, if combined with effective therapy, does reduce rates of\r\n\
    reoffending.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But this is the rub.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    While the government is effusive about the benefits of surveillance,\r\n\
    there\xE2\x80\x99s been no mention of increased funding for the evaluation and\r\n\
    provision of effective treatment for sex offenders. Yet is it critical\r\n\
    that such funding be provided, not only to ensure we get value from the\r\n\
    money spent on the bracelets, but because treatment is the best way to\r\n\
    make the community as safe as we can for children.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    According to Professor Thomson, money is desperately needed to both\r\n\
    properly evaluate which treatments work and to provide them to convicts\r\n\
    inside and outside the prison walls (where the temptation of real\r\n\
    children running around provides the one true test of cure).\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Until funds to do this work are found, we can\xE2\x80\x99t really look our children\r\n\
    in the eye and say we\xE2\x80\x99ve done all we can to make them safe.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Because the best way to avoid released prisoners re-offending is not to\r\n\
    track them, but to change them."
