attributes: 
  created_on: 2011-03-23 12:12:08
  slug: put-an-end-to-abortion-whispers
  site_id: "27"
  title: Put an End to Abortion Whispers
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:47:59
  content_markup: "<p>As Prime Minister John Howard put it: \xE2\x80\x9CYou can\xE2\x80\x99t have a situation where\n\
    every time somebody dares to express a view, they\xE2\x80\x99re jumped upon from a\n\
    great height and it\xE2\x80\x99s said the issue is back on the agenda.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>He\xE2\x80\x99s right. The country needs to take a few deep breaths, and a long\n\
    view on abortion politics.</p>\n\n\
    <p>We all know there is a strident coterie of conservative, misogynist men\n\
    in the inner circle of Government who are not only completely opposed to\n\
    women having a right to choose abortion at any stage of pregnancy, but\n\
    determined to do something about it.</p>\n\n\
    <p>What this means is that over the next few years we are going to be\n\
    hearing a lot from this powerful posse about female irresponsibility\n\
    when it comes to contraception. We\xE2\x80\x99ll be getting an earful about callous\n\
    feminist career-women who selfishly choose abortion instead of\n\
    motherhood, or depressed and regretful \xE2\x80\x9Cpost-abortive\xE2\x80\x9D women who\n\
    demonstrate the folly of society trusting the female of the species to\n\
    make important decisions about their own futures, and they\xE2\x80\x99ll be heaps\n\
    about the number of abortions that Australian women have. They\xE2\x80\x99ll be\n\
    more assertions than you can shake a stick at about the tragedy of\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Clate-term\xE2\x80\x9D abortions (a term that will never be defined but will be\n\
    applied to all terminations done after 12 or 14 weeks) and our ears will\n\
    be bashed with graphic descriptions of termination techniques used after\n\
    the first trimester.</p>\n\n\
    <p>It will be implied that abortion causes breast cancer despite the US\n\
    National Cancer Institute stating unequivocally in 2003 (based on a meta\n\
    analysis of all existing population-based, clinical and animal studies)\n\
    that \xE2\x80\x9Chaving an abortion or miscarriage does not increase a woman\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    subsequent risk of developing breast cancer\xE2\x80\x9D. It will be asserted that\n\
    abortion causes post-traumatic stress, despite Ronald Regan\xE2\x80\x99s Surgeon\n\
    General, the anti-choice C. Everett Koop, concluding that psychological\n\
    problems from abortion were \xE2\x80\x9Cminuscule from a public health\n\
    perspective\xE2\x80\x9D, and a panel of the American Psychological Foundation\n\
    concluding in 1989 that terminating an unwanted pregnancy posed no\n\
    hazard to women\xE2\x80\x99s mental health.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Questions will be raised about the safety of Mifepristone (RU 486), a\n\
    drug unavailable in Australia as a result of past anti-choice activism\n\
    despite it being used safely for many years by millions of women in at\n\
    least 19 countries. Assertions will be made about the unfairness of\n\
    making anti-choice taxpayers subsidize women\xE2\x80\x99s abortions through\n\
    Medicare (though the entitlement of bike-riders to withdraw their taxes\n\
    from the building of roads, will not be mentioned).</p>\n\n\
    <p>My point is twofold. First, we\xE2\x80\x99ve got a long, long way to go until the\n\
    next federal election. From this point until at least then &ndash; and maybe\n\
    longer, given current predictions about time needed for Labour to become\n\
    competitive again &ndash; we can feel confident that anti-choice Coalition\n\
    forces are going to use their power and influence in any way they can to\n\
    stir the pot on the abortion issue.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Are we going to jump every time any one of them says, \xE2\x80\x9Cboo\xE2\x80\x9D? Dance like\n\
    marionettes whenever they tug (the same old) string? How many times can\n\
    and should we \xE2\x80\x9Cdebate\xE2\x80\x9D the same issues, particularly when &ndash; despite all\n\
    the argy-bargy at the tail end of last year &ndash; a national public opinion\n\
    survey done by the ANU showed 81% of Australians agreeing that women\n\
    should have a right to choose?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Which brings me to my second point. Putting a question on notice (as\n\
    Boswell has done) is not \xE2\x80\x9Creigniting the debate.\xE2\x80\x9D Politicians repeating\n\
    their well-known personal views on the issue (as Beazley has done) is\n\
    not \xE2\x80\x9Cre-igniting the debate\xE2\x80\x9D. In fact, these contributions &ndash; such as\n\
    they are &ndash; are barely newsworthy. If I may quote dictionary.com, a\n\
    debate is a \xE2\x80\x9Cdiscussion involving opposing points\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But what is the \xE2\x80\x9Cpoint\xE2\x80\x9D of Boswell asking for precise numbers of\n\
    terminations, given he\xE2\x80\x99s among the crowd that thinks even one is too\n\
    many. Isn\xE2\x80\x99t it a foregone conclusion he\xE2\x80\x99ll conclude, no matter what\n\
    figure he gets, that it\xE2\x80\x99s too high? Thanks to the prolonged discussion\n\
    last year on the topic, we know what anti-choice MPs think about\n\
    abortion: they don\xE2\x80\x99t like them, or approve of the women who have them.\n\
    What we don\xE2\x80\x99t know is what the legislative intent is of the MPs who keep\n\
    doing whatever it takes to return abortion to the news. As co-conveners\n\
    of Emily\xE2\x80\x99s List Joan Kirner and Claire Moore put it yesterday, a public\n\
    debate on this issue run by politicians without any declared legislative\n\
    change is \xE2\x80\x9Cat best unnecessary and at worst misleading.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>What are anti-choice MPs plotting to do to women\xE2\x80\x99s freedom to get an\n\
    abortion? How are their secret plans going to affect the freedom of\n\
    Australian women and couples to decide for themselves if and when\n\
    they\xE2\x80\x99ll have children?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Such revelations would not only be newsworthy, they would provide the\n\
    information for a real debate, and a fair political battle, to begin.\n\
    Once the doors of all those prayer sessions and secret meetings are\n\
    flung open, Australian women and families will finally know &ndash; instead of\n\
    having to guess &ndash; precisely how their reproductive freedoms are going to\n\
    come under attack in the next few years. Experts will be able to\n\
    evaluate and make comment on how women and couples, from city and bush\n\
    and those of greater and lesser means, would be affected by mooted\n\
    administrative changes and legislative proposals. The media could ask\n\
    politicians to state their voting intentions, and Australian women and\n\
    couples would finally know how they, and those they love, are likely to\n\
    be affected by the changes proposed.</p>\n\n\
    <p>So let\xE2\x80\x99s stop the pseudo-debate, and let the real one begin.</p>\n"
