  title: "Book Review - Motherguilt: Australian women reveal their true feelings about motherhood"
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:47:49
  content_markup: "<p>Ita Buttrose &amp; Dr Penny Adams. Penguin/Viking, $32.95</p>\n\n\
    <p>TEASE: Motherguilt bills itself as a book in which Australian women\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Crevel their true feelings about motherhood\xE2\x80\x9D and one that assists women\n\
    to \xE2\x80\x9Cdeprogram themselves\xE2\x80\x9D from the powerful and unique \xE2\x80\x9Cepidemic of\n\
    guilt\xE2\x80\x9D experienced by today\xE2\x80\x99s mothers.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The strength of the book is the myriad of women\xE2\x80\x99s voices found on each\n\
    page. Both celebrity and \xE2\x80\x9Cordinary\xE2\x80\x9D mothers confess their parental sins\n\
    and doubts, and express their views on a wide range of maternal\n\
    experiences (mothering the \xE2\x80\x9Cnot-so-perfect\xE2\x80\x9D child, the experience of\n\
    breastfeeding, maternal competitiveness in the playgroup).</p>\n\n\
    <p>It\xE2\x80\x99s not easy for women to admit they\xE2\x80\x99ve found mothering unbearably\n\
    boring, or that they\xE2\x80\x99ve sometimes put their child\xE2\x80\x99s need second to their\n\
    own, when such admissions can lead them to be labelled a \xE2\x80\x9Cbad\xE2\x80\x9D mother.\n\
    Yet, 69-year old Jean risks this by sharing her disappointment with her\n\
    early mothering experience. \xE2\x80\x9CI can remember thinking,\xE2\x80\x9D, she recounts,\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9C\xE2\x80\x98If this is my life, my God, I\xE2\x80\x99d rather be dead\xE2\x80\x99.\xE2\x80\x9D Journalist Adele\n\
    Horin take us into her confidence with her tale of sending a sick child\n\
    to school so she could get to work, while presenter Joanna Griggs\n\
    confesses that she has the \xE2\x80\x9Ctime of her life\xE2\x80\x9D when away from her\n\
    children covering sport for Channel 7. As the authors rightly note,\n\
    women\xE2\x80\x99s sharing of their maternal battle stories \xE2\x80\x9Chas a curative power\n\
    all of its own\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Sadly, the rest of Motherguilt seems dedicated to wounding, rather than\n\
    healing. Instead of alleviating women\xE2\x80\x99s guilt feelings about motherhood,\n\
    it appears dedicated to affirming their current levels of moral angst,\n\
    or even making them worse. For example, the authors assert without a\n\
    shred of research evidence that contemporary mothers use abortion as\n\
    contraception, see babies as \xE2\x80\x9Cfashion accessories\xE2\x80\x9D and, in failing to be\n\
    relaxed and happy mothers, deny their children the carefree childhood\n\
    that is their \xE2\x80\x9Cinalienable right\xE2\x80\x9D. Stay-at-home mothers are castigated\n\
    for giving up their professional careers and allowing their kids\xE2\x80\x99 school\n\
    lives to take on exaggerated importance, as well as providing a poor\n\
    role model to their children by helping them cheat on homework\n\
    assignments.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But it is working mothers who really need to duck for cover. According\n\
    to the authors, their reliance on prepared and fast foods coupled with\n\
    their failure to serve up a family meal every night is the cause of\n\
    increased rates of childhood obesity; their busy lives and\n\
    competitiveness causes stressed, depressed and ADHD kids who miss out on\n\
    time to \xE2\x80\x9Cgaze at the clouds drifting by, watch a butterfly flit around\n\
    the garden or throw pebbles in a pond\xE2\x80\x9D; while their lack of time to\n\
    listen to their teenagers increases adolescent drinking and anorexia.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Similarly alarming \xE2\x80\x9Cfacts\xE2\x80\x9D and accusations appear throughout the book,\n\
    though they must always be taken on faith as no sources &ndash; either in the\n\
    text or in notes &ndash; are provided.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But most disturbing are the authors\xE2\x80\x99 conclusions about the causative\n\
    role contemporary mothers are playing in the downfall of the nation\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    children. This is Ita:</p>\n\n\
    <blockquote><p>The growth in children\xE2\x80\x99s illnesses and mood disturbances has occurred\n\
    in line with mothers\xE2\x80\x99 greater participation in the workforce. Could\n\
    this be coincidental? Can any intelligent woman seriously believe such\n\
    a thing without doubt of any kind? Surely it is impossible to overlook\n\
    something many mothers would prefer to close their eyes to &ndash; that\n\
    perhaps children have become the `victims\xE2\x80\x99 of the female ambition to\n\
    have it all.</p></blockquote>\n\n\
    <p>She continues:</p>\n\n\
    <blockquote><p>Many women got it wrong, and I include myself in this indictment. It\n\
    is all too obvious that children need more of their mother\xE2\x80\x99s time than\n\
    we have been able to give them\xE2\x80\xA6.Perhaps, most of all they need their\n\
    mums to be in less of a hurry\xE2\x80\xA6.If, as mothers, we need to feel guilty\n\
    about anything it is children. We have short-changed them. They have\n\
    been sending out signals for years now but we have preferred to be\n\
    blind to what has been going on.</p></blockquote>\n\n\
    <p>This quote tidily encapsulates all that is wrong with Motherguilt. The\n\
    unsupported alarmist claims; the uncritical acceptance of complex and\n\
    heavily-freighted ideas like \xE2\x80\x9Chaving it all\xE2\x80\x9D without any interrogation\n\
    of the sexist 1950s norms they encode; the imputation that children need\n\
    only their mothers and the corresponding silence about father-absence\n\
    and its impact on women\xE2\x80\x99s work and guilt-loads as well as children; the\n\
    firm yet tautological claim that the one thing mothers should feel\n\
    guilty about is children (what else would women feel motherguilt about?)</p>\n\n\
    <p>A recent letter to the Australian Book Review noted that \xE2\x80\x9Ceven a badly\n\
    written book has cost the author blood and sweat\xE2\x80\x9D. It was not a plea for\n\
    merciful reviewing, but could be read as one, and as a non-fiction\n\
    writer myself, I am sensitive to the harm done by a bad review.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But whatever compassion I feel for the authors, I feel much more for\n\
    their potential female readership. Indeed, I feel obligated to do what I\n\
    can to warn women of the disconnect between what this book promises and\n\
    what it delivers.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Because I just can\xE2\x80\x99t bear the thought of a young mother &ndash; anxious,\n\
    insecure, perhaps even teetering on the edge of depression &ndash; wandering\n\
    into her local bookshop in search of something that might help her to\n\
    understand her situation better and lift her spirits, leaving instead\n\
    with a load of Motherguilt.</p>\n"
