  title: Choice? What Choice?
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:47:43
  content_markup: "<p>Women academics under-achieving has nothing to do with biology or\n\
    inclination</p>\n\n\
    <p>Since the middle of January, when he theorised that an important reason\n\
    for the shortage of tenured female scientists and engineers in\n\
    American\xE2\x80\x99s top universities and researcher institutions was women\xE2\x80\x99s lack\n\
    of \xE2\x80\x9Cinstrinsic aptitude\xE2\x80\x9D, calls for his resignation have been coming\n\
    thick and fast. His defenders have fought back, insisting that Summers\n\
    has been unfairly shouted down by a politically correct cadre of\n\
    feminists.</p>\n\n\
    <p>A transcript of Summers\xE2\x80\x99 remarks on the Harvard website show his\n\
    speculation on the causes of female scientific and mathematical\n\
    under-achievement was three-pronged. Discrimination plays a small part,\n\
    Summers opined, but the rest of the problem could be slated home to\n\
    women\xE2\x80\x99s natural mediocrity (their under-representation in the left tail\n\
    of a bell curve measuring scientific and mathematical IQ), and their\n\
    unwillingness to work hard.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But while has been his claims about female biology that have caused him\n\
    so much grief, it was the Harvard President\xE2\x80\x99s \xE2\x80\x9Chigh-powered job\xE2\x80\x9D thesis\n\
    that really irked me.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Essentially, it re-badges institutional gender inequity as the morally\n\
    neutral consequences of women\xE2\x80\x99s work and family \xE2\x80\x9Cchoices\xE2\x80\x9D. High-powered\n\
    jobs, says Summer, demand 80 hour weeks, time flexibility, continuous\n\
    and diligent effort throughout the lifecycle and a mind that is \xE2\x80\x9Calways\n\
    working on the problems that are in the job, even when the job is not\n\
    taking place\xE2\x80\x9D. Married men, says Summers, have historically been more\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cprepared\xE2\x80\x9D to make this \xE2\x80\x9Ccommitment\xE2\x80\x9D than married women.</p>\n\n\
    <p>There\xE2\x80\x99s no doubt that the thesis that women (bless their deep and\n\
    karmically balanced souls) are \xE2\x80\x9Copting out\xE2\x80\x9D of the rat race and\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Credefining success\xE2\x80\x9D &ndash; rather than bashing their heads against iron\n\
    ceilings &ndash; is extremely popular at the moment. A 2003 cover story in the\n\
    New York Times Magazine put the case this way. Beneath a photo of a\n\
    mother and baby cuddling at the foot of a ladder, it asked \xE2\x80\x9CWhy don\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    more women get to the top?\xE2\x80\x9D. The answer: \xE2\x80\x9CThey choose not to.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Convenient? I\xE2\x80\x99ll say. But the trouble is that there\xE2\x80\x99s no evidence that\n\
    when mothers have real choice, they dump their plans to have the same\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Call\xE2\x80\x9D as men have always enjoyed and sedately file home. Instead, what\n\
    data there is suggests that when women do give up and accept life on the\n\
    Mummy-track, a lack of real options to balance work and family is the\n\
    cause.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The key to all this is the contrast between what choice looks like in\n\
    the abstract, versus its appearance in the real world. In the abstract,\n\
    unspoken and patently false presumptions about the full and fair context\n\
    in which women make decisions about career and family lead to\n\
    disinterested conclusions that women\xE2\x80\x99s failure to achieve is the\n\
    consequence of their work \xE2\x80\x9Cchoices\xE2\x80\x9D. In the real world, women know they\n\
    can only make authentic choices consistent with their needs and values\n\
    when there is an adequate range of high quality options available, and\n\
    they are free to decide between them.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Here\xE2\x80\x99s just some of what a 2004 US Government Accountability Office\n\
    report found when it asked women science students and academics why they\n\
    worked at smaller institutions, taught more, and more often on a\n\
    part-time basis: behaviour that they all knew significantly reduced\n\
    their odds of successfully competing against the men in their department\n\
    for tenure.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Firstly, most female PhD student said they intended to seek a position\n\
    at a small college, where they\xE2\x80\x99ll teach more and research less, in order\n\
    to maintain a work family balance. Secondly, women said they worked\n\
    part-time more often then men in order to juggle family life with a\n\
    tenure track position. Thirdly, they complained that because they\n\
    shoulder the bulk of the second shift at home but their male colleagues\n\
    don\xE2\x80\x99t, gender-neutral university assistance programs to parents &ndash; like\n\
    an extra year after a baby is born to publish before a tenure decision\n\
    is made &ndash; does nothing more than further advantage their male colleagues\n\
    in the tenure competition at their expense.</p>\n\n\
    <p>What all this, not to mention logic, suggests is that women \xE2\x80\x9Cchoose\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    their health, sanity and the well-being of their children and their\n\
    marriage against their own career advancement in the same way animals\n\
    caught in steel trap traps \xE2\x80\x9Cchoose\xE2\x80\x9D to gnaw of their legs.</p>\n\n\
    <p>And when women aren\xE2\x80\x99t trapped? Anecdotal evidence (and that\xE2\x80\x99s most of\n\
    what\xE2\x80\x99s around, given the dearth of high-quality family-friendly\n\
    employment) suggests that they stay, excel, and achieve.</p>\n\n\
    <p>In fact, the only real chance of ever testing Summers\xE2\x80\x99 thesis about the\n\
    role biology plays in women\xE2\x80\x99s work patterns is to eliminate the effect\n\
    gender discrimination and bias has on them. Only when the playing field\n\
    is truly level &ndash; both at home and at work &ndash; will we know whether men\n\
    keep rising to the top because they really are the cream.</p>\n"
