    its unique hippy cosmopolitan groove indirectly through the\r\n\
    matter-of-fact way she describes some of its more bizarre denizens.\r\n\
    Like, for instance, Pan and his half-feral cross-dressing band of male\r\n\
    faeries who rescue Zac after a failed ocean suicide attempt. The\r\n\
    following morning, Zac wakes to find himself in a house that is\r\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Csingle-handedly holding back the advance of the rainforest\xE2\x80\x9D near a\r\n\
    make-shift dome enclosing \xE2\x80\x9Ca solemn circle of seven men and women and a\r\n\
    small, smoky fire\xE2\x80\x9D. Just then a man dressed as a woman in a gold\r\n\
    cocktail gown and a pink feather boa, totters into view. \xE2\x80\x9CYoo hoo! Pan!\r\n\
    I\xE2\x80\x99m late as usual. I lost my fucking eyelash on your fucking muddy path.\r\n\
    When are you going to get a man to do some work about the place?\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Less convincing are the over-wordy riffs about and to the place\r\n\
    sprinkled liberally - and unnecessarily - throughout the text. Riffs\r\n\
    that sometimes run for pages with lines like \xE2\x80\x9CWelcome to Byron Bay, so\r\n\
    beautiful it will make you weep\xE2\x80\x9D and \xE2\x80\x9CYou are the gazuumper on the dream\r\n\
    home, the developer who buys the last of the breach front land.\xE2\x80\x9D I also\r\n\
    grew to detest the subheadings scattered liberally through each chapter.\r\n\
    At best, they unnecessarily foreshadowed events (like the one entitled\r\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9CFoccacia\xE2\x80\x9D that keyed me into the fact that the next few paragraphs\r\n\
    would contain someone eating one). At worst, they were eye-rollingly\r\n\
    twee, like the \xE2\x80\x9CYou Give Me Fever\xE2\x80\x9D one preceding Zac\xE2\x80\x99s sweat-drenched\r\n\
    awakening to a serous flu-like illness. Occasionally, a smug omnipotent\r\n\
    narrator creeps into the third-person voice, begging the question of his\r\n\
    or her identity and source of knowledge about the characters\xE2\x80\x99 pasts and\r\n\
    futures. For all such errors of judgement, I am more inclined to blame\r\n\
    editor than author. It is the latter\xE2\x80\x99s job to take risks, and the\r\n\
    formers to indicate when these succeed and fail.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    And sometimes Blackadder\xE2\x80\x99s risks do succeed. Throughout the book is the\r\n\
    motif of the stalking hand of death whose needs must be satiated to\r\n\
    balance the books of fate. When Zac evades death\xE2\x80\x99s grasp in the early\r\n\
    pages of the book, an aging whale succumbs instead, the mourning cries\r\n\
    of its pod filling the ocean with sadness. Later, it is the life of a\r\n\
    young girl whose story intersects with that of the mysterious Black\r\n\
    Dragon that is snatched in the place of the new relationships, lives and\r\n\
    possibilities that have emerged since the party. None too original, but\r\n\
    Blackadder carries it off well, adding to After the Party\xE2\x80\x99s cosmic\r\n\
    beating-of-the-butterfly\xE2\x80\x99s-wings theme of the interconnectedness of\r\n\
    nature and those linked through the bonds of love."
