    by 1988 Victorian legislation that controversially entitles anonymous\r\n\
    donors to set in train processes that will lead their biological child\r\n\
    to become aware that they were conceived by donor gametes, turn 18.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    While we may not agree with all the reasons parents have for delaying or\r\n\
    deciding against disclosure, some may engender our sympathy. Parents\r\n\
    fear their child will be distressed to discover a lack of genetic link\r\n\
    with one or both of them, particularly when, as is the case for some\r\n\
    children, information about the donor is scant. The non-biological\r\n\
    parent - usually the father - may worry his child will love him less\r\n\
    when she learns there is no biological link, or that others will see the\r\n\
    family as less than \xE2\x80\x9Cnormal\xE2\x80\x9D. And some parents are simply so\r\n\
    uncomfortable talking about sex, that the prospect of having to explain\r\n\
    to their little ones the more complex reproductive arrangements that\r\n\
    prevailed in their situation daunt them into silence.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    In most Western countries, including Australia, the law tends to allow\r\n\
    parents to make their own decisions - according to their own values -\r\n\
    about what is in the best interests of their offspring. The only\r\n\
    exception is when the courts are convinced the parent\xE2\x80\x99s decision is\r\n\
    putting their child\xE2\x80\x99s health and safety at risk. By allowing donors to\r\n\
    set in train processes that will reveal to a child that he or she is\r\n\
    donor-conceived, the State government has asserted what it believes is\r\n\
    in a child\xE2\x80\x99s best interests, and forced the hand of parents of\r\n\
    donor-conceived children in the direction of telling. Whether parental\r\n\
    denial of knowledge about genetic origins really does threaten a child\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    health and safety to a degree that such intervention is justified, or\r\n\
    whether it wrongly establishes donor-conceived families as second-class\r\n\
    ones, is a matter for debate.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The reality for parents of donor-conceived children, however, is that\r\n\
    changing social, medical realities make secret keeping an increasingly\r\n\
    risky proposition. Victorian parents must be mindful that July is around\r\n\
    the corner. If their child is among the first crop of donor-conceived\r\n\
    kids affected by Victoria\xE2\x80\x99s prevailing legal regime, the time to tell is\r\n\
    now.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The Infertility Treatment Authority (ITA) administers the regulation of\r\n\
    infertility treatment in Victoria. The ITA offers information and\r\n\
    support to parents deciding if, when and how to tell children the full\r\n\
    story of their conception. More information about telling can be found\r\n\
    at [www.ita.org.au](http://www.ita.org.au/)."
