  title: Rewind
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:50:30
  content_markup: "<p>The recent \xE2\x80\x9CCamilla\xE2\x80\x9D incident streamed from the Big Brother house\n\
    several weeks ago renewed controversy about the show\xE2\x80\x99s suitability for\n\
    free-to-air TV.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Of course for some, the issue was decided long ago. Victorian Family\n\
    Council Secretary Bill Muelenberg, Family First Senator Senator Steven\n\
    Fielding and Queensland Nationals MP Paul Neville have long condemned\n\
    the show as sleazy and dangerously sexually licentious. In the wake of\n\
    the weekend\xE2\x80\x99s \xE2\x80\x9Cincident\xE2\x80\x9D, this conga line was joined by the leaders of\n\
    both major parties. The Opposition Leader lamented the show\xE2\x80\x99s treatment\n\
    of young women, while the Prime Minister asked Channel Ten to take the\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cstupid program\xE2\x80\x9D off air.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Are calls for media self-censorship evidence of feminist inroads into\n\
    the sensibilities of the nation\xE2\x80\x99s leaders, the relentless crusade of\n\
    Christian moralists to control what the rest of us see, hear and read,\n\
    or just plain commonsense? Was the two minutes that shook the world in\n\
    the collective bedroom of the Big Brother household evidence of the\n\
    depravity of today\xE2\x80\x99s male youth, or just how far &ndash; in the sexual\n\
    politics stakes &ndash; they\xE2\x80\x99ve come?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Deciding requires us to disentangle the varied business and moral\n\
    mandates in play. From a commercial point of view, it\xE2\x80\x99s arguable that\n\
    Channel 10 had little choice but to follow the advice of media studies\n\
    academic Catherine Lumby and evict the men from the house for being on\n\
    the wrong side of what Lumby described as the line dividing \xE2\x80\x9Csexual\n\
    behaviour and sexual assault\xE2\x80\x9D. The recent axing of Big Brother Adults\n\
    after pressure from Coalition MPs proved the not inconsiderable sway of\n\
    the Christian right in this country, and appeasing them by turfing the\n\
    men out and inviting the Queensland police to investigate made good\n\
    business sense.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The network\xE2\x80\x99s response, however, says little about whether the behaviour\n\
    of the two men merited condemnation on moral grounds. Lumby said the men\n\
    were guilty of sexual assault, while Communications Minister Helen\n\
    Coonan charged them with objectifying women. But in all the frenetic\n\
    tut-tutting that surrounded the case, few have considered whether the\n\
    young men\xE2\x80\x99s response to Camilla\xE2\x80\x99s objection to their unquestionably\n\
    inappropriate behaviour shows a solid understanding of the key feminist\n\
    principle that whatever she wears and wherever she goes, when a woman\n\
    says \xE2\x80\x9Cno\xE2\x80\x9D, she means \xE2\x80\x9Cno\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The footage confirms Big Brother\xE2\x80\x99s deliberate construction of sexually\n\
    charged situations that the young people of the house are expected to\n\
    smoothly and consistently negotiate before a national audience. In the\n\
    moments leading up the incident, Camilla &ndash; wearing underwear and a\n\
    cleavage-revealing skivvy &ndash; slides into John and Ash\xE2\x80\x99s bed. A moment\n\
    later, John\xE2\x80\x99s arm is pressing her to the bed, while Ash appears to whip\n\
    out his genitals and rub them in her face. This part of the story we\n\
    know.</p>\n\n\
    <p>What has received less attention is what comes next. Camilla vocally\n\
    objects to what is happening to her and the lads withdraw, immediately\n\
    and fully.</p>\n\n\
    <p>There is no question that John and Ash\xE2\x80\x99s forceful act of restraint and\n\
    sexual domination of</p>\n\n\
    <p>Camilla should not &ndash; without her express and prior permission &ndash; have\n\
    taken place. For this, they owed her a sincere and profound apology.\n\
    However, it seems an act of deliberate blindness to ignore the alacrity\n\
    with which the men responded to her insistence that they back off.\n\
    Surveys continue to show a disturbing number of men continue to believe\n\
    women really mean \xE2\x80\x9Cyes\xE2\x80\x9D when they say \xE2\x80\x9Cno\xE2\x80\x9D. John and Ash, however, don\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    appear to be among them.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Maintaining consent as the key arbiter of what constitutes assault or\n\
    otherwise deviant behaviour is critical to preserving the liberation of\n\
    female desire and sexuality for which second-generation feminists\n\
    strove. Women can fancy a threesome, dig S&amp; M or fantasise about\n\
    gerbils. As long as they are competent, and freely give their consent,\n\
    neither the label \xE2\x80\x9Cvictim\xE2\x80\x9D or \xE2\x80\x9Cslut\xE2\x80\x9D should apply.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The opposing point of view &ndash; endorsed by an uneasy colation of radical\n\
    anti-porn feminist and Christian crusaders &ndash; is that some (mostly male)\n\
    sexual behaviour is intrinsically aggressive or otherwise sinful, and\n\
    needs to be curtailed, for the sake of women and/or civilisation as a\n\
    whole.</p>\n\n\
    <p>We can laugh at the arrogance and narrow-mindedness of such views, but\n\
    the barbarians are at the gate. Maintaining individual control over what\n\
    we watch, the privacy of our bedroom and how we define and express our\n\
    desires and capacities as men and women requires that we consistently\n\
    affirm, in art as well as in life, the important of consent in defining\n\
    what we do &ndash; and is done to us \xE2\x80\x94 as right or wrong.</p>\n"
