    tellingly to the preference of his compatriots for somewhat, rather and\r\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Ca bit\xE2\x80\x9D. In a telling interview with Andrew Denton in 2003, replayed on\r\n\
    ABC TV last night as a tribute, Irwin frankly acknowledged the\r\n\
    embarrassment he caused his compatriots. I\xE2\x80\x99m embarrassing, he explained\r\n\
    because \xE2\x80\x9Cthere\xE2\x80\x99s a little bit of me in everybody\xE2\x80\x9D. In addition, what\r\n\
    Irwin called the \xE2\x80\x9Cyeah, yeah, take it or leave it\xE2\x80\x9D attitude of Aussies\r\n\
    to everything, made them uncomfortable with his passionate embrace of\r\n\
    everything.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    He may have only got it half right. As far as I can see, there\xE2\x80\x99s way too\r\n\
    little of Irwin in most of us. Not only do we know it, we work damn hard\r\n\
    to keep it that way, for precisely the reasons Irwin nominates: our fear\r\n\
    of appearing too invested in or excited about anything. It\xE2\x80\x99s all\r\n\
    terribly English, really. Being so relaxed we\xE2\x80\x99re horizontal is a highly\r\n\
    esteemed Australian characteristic, and if the upshot of our commitment\r\n\
    to indifference is a loss of our own passion for the things that really\r\n\
    matter to us, and a disdain for the untrammelled enthusiasm of others,\r\n\
    than so be it.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Are we afraid of failure? This is the classic analysis of those afraid\r\n\
    of trying too hard, but I think what stymies us is more pedestrian: a\r\n\
    fear of the unpredictable and potentially uncomfortable social\r\n\
    situations that could result if people drop roles and abandon lines.\r\n\
    Wild, larger-than-life characters like Irwin - hyper-extraverts - are\r\n\
    unpredictable; you never know what they might say or do. They could ask\r\n\
    you for something you don\xE2\x80\x99t want to give, or beg conflict by saying\r\n\
    something you don\xE2\x80\x99t want to hear. They must be subdued through ridicule\r\n\
    or marginalisation, or frozen out completely to manage our collective\r\n\
    fear of the awkward moment.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Americans have no such fear, and this may partially explain their\r\n\
    unequivocal hero-worship of Irwin. In fact, I suspect the real source of\r\n\
    American\xE2\x80\x99s love-affair with Irwin was not what made him Australian, but\r\n\
    the Americanness of much of his personality. Hyper-extraversion, and its\r\n\
    superlative sidekicks of uncontained passion and enthusiasm, are what\r\n\
    Americans love and admire about themselves. How flattering to see them\r\n\
    emulated by the nation\xE2\x80\x99s good friends Down Under, and in a cute Aussie\r\n\
    accent to boot.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    It is perhaps testament to the complexity of the Australian character\r\n\
    that while Irwin\xE2\x80\x99s energy and passion made us anxious, we also admired\r\n\
    it. Many, myself included, couldn\xE2\x80\x99t help but feel terribly fond of the\r\n\
    man. As he told Denton, he was the boy who never grew up, and we\r\n\
    couldn\xE2\x80\x99t help but smile at his boundless enthusiasm and energy,\r\n\
    childlike faith in his invincibility when it came to animal stings or\r\n\
    bites, and his inability to be other than himself or to even waste time\r\n\
    trying.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    He was one out of the box, and I know I\xE2\x80\x99m going to miss him like hell."
