    choices - of those pursuing control over their bodies and their deaths.\r\n\
    Palliative care providers, argues a recent article in Palliative\r\n\
    Medicine, deem all patients who \xE2\x80\x9Cthink that their life is irretrievably\r\n\
    bad\xE2\x80\x9D to be \xE2\x80\x9Cwrong\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Finally, both advocacy groups suggest that the availability of more\r\n\
    options has the counter-intuitive outcome of reducing choice. The mere\r\n\
    availability of abortion and physician-assisted suicide, the argument\r\n\
    runs, coerces women and terminally ill-patients to \xE2\x80\x9Cchoose it\xE2\x80\x9D so as to\r\n\
    avoid burdening others with their need. Real choice, it is claimed,\r\n\
    requires the continued criminalisation of abortion and\r\n\
    physician-assisted suicide so that more legitimate options like adoption\r\n\
    and palliative care can flourish.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    So what is the truth? Surveys across the western world, including\r\n\
    Australia, clearly show support for a right to die. A 2002 Gallup poll\r\n\
    found 72% of Americans supported doctor-assisted suicide for those with\r\n\
    terminal illnesses, while in the same year 70% of Australians were found\r\n\
    to be in favour of giving terminally ill and severely suffering people a\r\n\
    choice about the timing and method of their death.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Data from Oregon suggests that the most frequently given reasons for\r\n\
    choosing physician-assisted suicide by the approximately 30 people who\r\n\
    die this way every year are loss of autonomy\" (87%), \xE2\x80\x9Closs of dignity\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    (80%) and \xE2\x80\x9Closs of the ability to enjoy the activities that make life\r\n\
    worth living\xE2\x80\x9D (84%). This data, which suggests that mental rather than\r\n\
    physical suffering is the main driver of decisions to die, undermines\r\n\
    the assertion of anti-euthanasia forces that the effectiveness of\r\n\
    modern-day palliative methods obviates the need for legal reform.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Such figures also undercut claims that the legal freedom to die would\r\n\
    exert the greatest coercive pressure on those lacking options other than\r\n\
    death: namely, the ill-educated and those too poor to afford palliative\r\n\
    care. The overwhelming majority of Oregonians seeking physician-assisted\r\n\
    suicide were highly educated and well off. Indeed, 86% were enrolled in\r\n\
    hospice care at the time of their suicides, while only 2 of the 208\r\n\
    people who have used the legislation so far were uninsured.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    There are some values that palliative care and right to die advocates\r\n\
    share. These include a belief in the importance of reducing human\r\n\
    suffering and a distaste for the over-medicalisation of the dying\r\n\
    process.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    However, disagreements between the two groups are profound. They include\r\n\
    theoretical disputes about the legitimacy of death as a choice as well\r\n\
    as more empirically-based spats about the competence and capacity of the\r\n\
    terminally ill to make adequately informed decisions, and the likely\r\n\
    effect of making physician-assisted suicide a legal choice. Palliative\r\n\
    care advocates see decriminalisation as an invitation to what Melbourne\r\n\
    writer Juliette Hughes (Opinion, 13/7) recently described as a culture\r\n\
    of death that would enable the preferences of greedy relatives and\r\n\
    stingy hospital bureaucrats to be privileged above those of vulnerable\r\n\
    patients. In contrast, advocates for physician-assisted suicide believe\r\n\
    safeguards can be put in place to protect patient-autonomy and reduce\r\n\
    the risks of involuntary euthanasia: risks currently managed in\r\n\
    secretive and ad hoc ways. One survey found that while 30% of all\r\n\
    Australian deaths involving a medical decision designed to end the\r\n\
    patient\xE2\x80\x99s life, only 4% of these decisions were in response to a direct\r\n\
    request from the patient.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Some Australians speed and drive drunk. Yet few would seriously moot the\r\n\
    criminalisation of driving as a solution to this undeniably serious\r\n\
    problem.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Instead, as we do to minimise the risk of irresponsible driving to self\r\n\
    and others, we must move to enact sophisticated regulatory and\r\n\
    compliance regimes around end of life decisions. Ones that will offer\r\n\
    those of us who meet threshold conditions for competence to exercise our\r\n\
    reason and our values when it comes to critical decisions about our\r\n\
    bodies, our lives and our deaths."
