    \r\n\
    Religious leaders are no amateurs when it comes to defending male\r\n\
    privilege in the liturgy and hierarchy. \xE2\x80\x9COur holy books command us to\r\n\
    treat women this way,\xE2\x80\x9D they protest, conveniently forgetting the\r\n\
    redundancy of scriptural commandments to stone adulterers, or forcibly\r\n\
    marry rapists to their victims. Alternatively, they argue that if women\r\n\
    weren\xE2\x80\x99t content with second-class citizenship, they\xE2\x80\x99d have fled the\r\n\
    churches long ago.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Would that it were so simple. As the recent expose on ABC\xE2\x80\x99s Four Corners\r\n\
    made clear, the fundamentalist Exclusive Brethren exact high costs -\r\n\
    such as life-long separation from spouses and children - from those who\r\n\
    exit. It is also unclear whether a guarantee of more realistic exit\r\n\
    rights is a just response to unlawful discrimination by religious\r\n\
    orders.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Would we deem \xE2\x80\x9Clump it or leave\xE2\x80\x9D an acceptable response to Aboriginal\r\n\
    Australians who complained that their church was denying them leadership\r\n\
    positions and demanding they sit in pews at the back? Or would we feel\r\n\
    that Aborigines have a right to membership in a church free of\r\n\
    institutionalised racism.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Sexism is just as eviscerating to the dignity, self-esteem, aspirations\r\n\
    and opportunities of women as racism is to people of colour. It was the\r\n\
    recognition of this fact that led to the passage of the Federal Sex\r\n\
    Discrimination Act in 1984. More than 20 years later, it is high time\r\n\
    its provisions were fully enforced."
