    Alzheimer\xE2\x80\x99s and the sorts of spinal cord injuries suffered by the late\r\n\
    actor Christopher Reeves. Pluripotent cells may one day allow us to\r\n\
    produce blood, and grow organs like hearts and livers that - because\r\n\
    they are genetically matched to the patient - will eliminate the need\r\n\
    for anti-rejection drugs.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The crux of George\xE2\x80\x99s claim is that this research cannot be done without\r\n\
    eggs, and this means that women will be coerced into donating them. The\r\n\
    solution she proposes is to ban the technologies in Australia, despite\r\n\
    her knowledge that stem cell research will continue in places like the\r\n\
    UK, Canada, New Zealand, Sweden, Finland and Spain.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    How will such coercion happen? In a submission opposing the passage of\r\n\
    legislation designed to allow Australian scientists greater freedom to\r\n\
    pursue stem cell cures, WFA said that if eggs are allowed to be sold,\r\n\
    poor women will have no choice but to donate against their will.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    A valid claim, except for the fact that the legislation - to be debated\r\n\
    in the Senate next week - explicitly prohibits the sale of eggs, sperms\r\n\
    or embryos. Those guilty of inducing egg donation by offers of cash, a\r\n\
    discount on treatment or even giving priority in the provision of\r\n\
    service risk up to 10 years in jail.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Women\xE2\x80\x99s Forum Australia also claims that women will be coerced into\r\n\
    donating by their desire to be seen as \xE2\x80\x9Cgood women\xE2\x80\x9D. Their submission\r\n\
    says that \xE2\x80\x9Csocial and cultural expectations of feminine self-sacriifice\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    will lead women to \xE2\x80\x9Csacrifice their own interests, and assume the health\r\n\
    risks of ova extraction for the sake of others\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    In fact, women already donate eggs. In 2003 196 Victorian women gave\r\n\
    their eggs to women they knew, although a small number donated to\r\n\
    strangers.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Is Women\xE2\x80\x99s Forum Australia saying these women didn\xE2\x80\x99t really choose to\r\n\
    make such donations, but were simply trying to look like \xE2\x80\x9Cgood women\xE2\x80\x9D in\r\n\
    the eyes of others? If such altruism should be banned when it comes to\r\n\
    stem cell science, shouldn\xE2\x80\x99t women be prohibited from donating eggs to\r\n\
    women facing infertility, too?\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Women also donate blood, though this - like all medical procedures -\r\n\
    carries risks. Should the state also step in here and say \xE2\x80\x9Cno\xE2\x80\x9D?\r\n\
    \r\n\
    How would any of us feel to be told that we cannot donate an egg to a\r\n\
    sister suffering infertility or to a stem cell research project\r\n\
    attempting to cure a disease from which we, or a beloved child, suffers?\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The answer is infantilized, patronized, and mad as hell. If George\r\n\
    thinks egg donation is too risky, she has the right to say \xE2\x80\x9Cno\xE2\x80\x9D. What\r\n\
    she doesn\xE2\x80\x99t deserve is the freedom to stop me, or any other women,\r\n\
    making my own risk/benefit calculation, and my own choice.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Which takes us back to our first question: is stem cell science\r\n\
    anti-woman? The clear answer is \xE2\x80\x9Cno.\xE2\x80\x9D Researchers and scientists believe\r\n\
    that as long as relevant legal rulings and ethical guidelines are\r\n\
    followed, women have the same ability to give - or withhold - informed\r\n\
    consent to being involved as men.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Curiously, the sole source of sexism in the debate comes from groups\r\n\
    asserting feminist credentials. Women\xE2\x80\x99s Forum Australia describes itself\r\n\
    as an \xE2\x80\x9Cindependent thinktank\xE2\x80\x9D that promotes \xE2\x80\x9Cthe advancement, well-being\r\n\
    and freedom of all women\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The directors of WFA include the \xE2\x80\x9Cbioethical advisor\xE2\x80\x9D to former pro-life\r\n\
    Senator Brian Harradine, two women - including George - with links to\r\n\
    Opus Dei and a Southern Cross Bioethics Institute (SCBI) staff member.\r\n\
    SCBI is the research arm of Southern Cross Care, which is the product of\r\n\
    the Knights of the Southern Cross, an order of Catholic men \xE2\x80\x9Ccommitted\r\n\
    to promoting the Christian way of life throughout Australia\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Defining \xE2\x80\x9Cindependent\xE2\x80\x9D is tricky, but there is little doubt that\r\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cthinktanks\xE2\x80\x9D should do good thinking.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The factual sloppiness and offensively sexist nature of arguments\r\n\
    advanced by George don\xE2\x80\x99t fit the bill."
