    messages of \xE2\x80\x9Cdo\xE2\x80\x9D (eat healthy foods) and \xE2\x80\x9Cdesert\xE2\x80\x9D (as in, you deserve\r\n\
    it) that connect self-nurture with the bodily well-being necessary to\r\n\
    enjoy the good things in life.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Positive messages are also more likely to be effective in promoting\r\n\
    behavioural change, and insofar as they focus more on the importance of\r\n\
    staying active rather than on what we eat, may even be more consistent\r\n\
    with the medical evidence. Paul Campos, Professor of law at the\r\n\
    University of Colorado and author of The Obesity Myth argues that\r\n\
    activity is a better predictor of health than weight and that \xE2\x80\x9CThere is\r\n\
    no good evidence that significant long-term weight loss is beneficial to\r\n\
    health\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    We need to speak to our children, and about them, in ways that make our\r\n\
    love for them, and approval of the people they are becoming, crystal\r\n\
    clear. Teaching them how to nurture themselves by eating healthy food\r\n\
    and participating in physical activity they enjoy is the most ethical\r\n\
    and effective way for us as parents, and as a society, to offer them the\r\n\
    gift of good health."
