  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:57:35
  content_markup: "<p>In Viro Fertility Goddess by Jodi Panayotov. Blink Press, June 2007, pp.\n\
    218. ISBN 978~~0~~9803110~~0~~6</p>\n\n\
    <p>TEASE: Infertility sucks and IVF is worse. Yet women rarely talk about\n\
    either, or make jokes, a truth Jodi Panayotov found out the hard way\n\
    when aged 37 she struggled to get pregnant and to stay that way.</p>\n\n\
    <p>It never fails to amaze me the insensitive things people say to women\n\
    who, after a few years of wedded bliss, fail to spawn. The comment by\n\
    Panayotov\xE2\x80\x99s fellow stewardess is typical. \xE2\x80\x9CYou\xE2\x80\x99ve been married for years\n\
    now, when are you going to have a baby?\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>How I wish all women would react as Panayotov did that day. \xE2\x80\x9CActually, I\n\
    just lost one, miscarriage you know.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>When a non-pregnant stewardess approaches Panayotov shortly after this\n\
    incident to confide that she\xE2\x80\x99d also had a miscarriage but had only told\n\
    her family about it, Panayotov responds with a question revelatory of\n\
    the driving motivation behind In Vitro Fertility Goddess. \xE2\x80\x9CWhy is it we\n\
    don\xE2\x80\x99t talk about it? It\xE2\x80\x99s like there \xE2\x80\x98s a hidden code of silence of\n\
    something. I\xE2\x80\x99ve never in ten years of working here heard of one\n\
    miscarriage. And I\xE2\x80\x99ve heard all about every birth.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>In Vitro Fertility Goddess is Panayotov\xE2\x80\x99s attempt to talk, even laugh,\n\
    about the reproductive difficulties faced by she and her husband Michel.\n\
    From the early days of her journey where repeated miscarriages saw her\n\
    join \xE2\x80\x9Cthe freakish underclass somewhere between the Fertile and\n\
    Infertile\xE2\x80\x9D that only exists on \xE2\x80\x9Cobscure websites\xE2\x80\x9D because \xE2\x80\x9Cnobody\xE2\x80\xA6admits\n\
    to being [a] member,\xE2\x80\x9D to Panayotov\xE2\x80\x99s reluctant commencement of IVF,\n\
    Infertility Treatment Goddess contributes to the growing recognition\n\
    that women suffer psychic and physical costs not just when they are\n\
    unable to control their bodies and their lives in order to avoid having\n\
    children, but when such control eludes them when they try to conceive.</p>\n\n\
    <p>In Vitro Fertility Goddess has much going for it. Taking a stylistic\n\
    leaf out of Bridget Jones\xE2\x80\x99s Diary it is at times laugh-out-loud funny. A\n\
    medical receptionist retreats when a miscarrying Panayotov yells at her,\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cas if a large dog has mounted and is attempting to have sex with her.\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    When Panayotov confesses to seeing a herbalist to cure her fertility\n\
    woes, her IVF doctor goes \xE2\x80\x9Call quiet,\xE2\x80\x9D as if she were confessing to\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cjoining the Branch Davidians or something.\xE2\x80\x9D And like Brigette Jones, it\n\
    promises and delivers an insight into the minds of women whose\n\
    circumstances rather than choices have derailed their lives from\n\
    conventional female courses, and a conclusion (one we know about from\n\
    the start courtesy of the mother-baby photo gracing the book\xE2\x80\x99s back\n\
    cover) that rewards the heroine\xE2\x80\x99s struggles with happy-ever-afters.</p>\n\n\
    <p>What works less well is the unevenness of the book\xE2\x80\x99s tone and style, the\n\
    unreflective way the text conflates embryos and babies and the\n\
    unmitigated bitchyness of the author\xE2\x80\x99s lambasting of fertile women as\n\
    either \xE2\x80\x9Csmug pregnants\xE2\x80\x9D or selfish aborters whose mere existence\n\
    demonstrates an insensitivity to Panayotov\xE2\x80\x99s plight that makes her wish\n\
    to purchase a voodoo doll so she can prick them in effigy.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Few, if any of these not insubstantial problems, are Panayotov\xE2\x80\x99s fault.\n\
    Authors are not editors, and this book reads like the first draft a\n\
    promising manuscript, rather than the final text of a published work.\n\
    Grammatical errors, contradictions and repetitiveness (we are told twice\n\
    about a neighbour\xE2\x80\x99s front window sticker welcoming dogs but not\n\
    children, and as many times about the unsavoury details of the clinic\n\
    masturbation room in which husband Michel fulfils his end of the IVF\n\
    bargain), the loss of Bridget Jones voice during parts of the narration\n\
    and a complete absence of humour during what was clearly the most\n\
    emotionally trying part of the Panayotovs\xE2\x80\x99 journey to parenthood are\n\
    just the sort of problems the editorial process is designed to identify\n\
    and assist the author to address.</p>\n\n\
    <p>That it failed to do so, and that Panayotov\xE2\x80\x99s editor was her husband\n\
    Michel, not only underscores the essential nature of editing to the\n\
    production of quality Australian literary works, but the need for that\n\
    editorial input to be professional: both skilled and impartial.</p>\n"
