  slug: in-death-we-dont-part-from-our-obligations
  site_id: "27"
  title: "In Death We Don\xE2\x80\x99t Part from our Obligations"
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:55:40
  content_markup: "<p>Last week in New Zealand, Ivy May Ngahooro became the third body\n\
    snatched after disputes about burial between non-indigenous and Maori\n\
    relatives. The distress of Ms Ngahooro\xE2\x80\x99s family was extensively covered\n\
    in the New Zealand press, with the will\xE2\x80\x99s executor, niece Trish Scoble,\n\
    saying that the loss of the body made her feel both \xE2\x80\x9Csick\xE2\x80\x9D and\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cfrightened\xE2\x80\x9D. Scoble said that she would not stop until her Auntie May\n\
    was laid to rest as she had wanted.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The body snatching cases raises interesting legal issues. One is that\n\
    because New Zealand (like Australia) does not recognize bodies as\n\
    property, the unauthorized removal of Ngahooro\xE2\x80\x99s remains did not\n\
    constitute theft or justify police intervention (though lawmakers in New\n\
    Zealand now appear ready to change this).</p>\n\n\
    <p>The moral issues are just as compelling. For some, the Auntie May case\n\
    was a storm in a teacup. Who cared where the woman was buried? Auntie\n\
    May wouldn\xE2\x80\x99t because she was dead.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But is it really that simple? Can we simply disregard the wishes of the\n\
    deceased? Or are there things we owe to the dead?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Many moral thinkers, including Aristotle and Confucius, believed we did\n\
    have obligations to the dead. Every time we refuse to speak ill of them\n\
    or work to carry out their last wishes or insist they get justice when\n\
    their demise was the result of foul play, we strenuously agree.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But while we know that it would be wrong to override Dad\xE2\x80\x99s request to be\n\
    an organ donor or for staff at the morgue to violate Mum\xE2\x80\x99s body, it\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    hard to explain why. After all, being dead, neither Dad nor Mum are\n\
    likely to care.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But the end of a body doesn\xE2\x80\x99t mean the end of a relationship. Just\n\
    because my mother\xE2\x80\x99s dead doesn\xE2\x80\x99t mean she\xE2\x80\x99s not my mother. So while the\n\
    relationship demands of the dead are few, what demands there are can be\n\
    said to create obligations in the living.</p>\n\n\
    <p>In the same way that relationships carry forward beyond death, so too do\n\
    the interests of the dead person. It\xE2\x80\x99s not hard to see why dead people\n\
    would maintain an interest in the fate of their body and organs, and the\n\
    protection of their memory, legacy and reputation. The law recognizes\n\
    these things by enforcing the terms of the deceased\xE2\x80\x99s will.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The fact that the dead won\xE2\x80\x99t know of our failure to protect their\n\
    interests doesn\xE2\x80\x99t mean those interests don\xE2\x80\x99t exist, and our failure\n\
    doesn\xE2\x80\x99t count. If you pledge fidelity to your partner when you marry,\n\
    then sleeping with someone else make you a cheat and causes your partner\n\
    hurt, even if they never find out. And if you don\xE2\x80\x99t scatter Dad\xE2\x80\x99s ashes\n\
    in the Blue Mountains like he asked, the fact that he\xE2\x80\x99ll never know\n\
    doesn\xE2\x80\x99t mean he wasn\xE2\x80\x99t harmed when you let him down.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The upshot? That even if the dead don\xE2\x80\x99t know we\xE2\x80\x99ve harmed them, they\n\
    have legitimate interests that can be harmed. These interests are ones\n\
    those of us bound by relationship to the dead are obligated to defend.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Of course, many of the laws and customs surrounding death protect the\n\
    interests and wellbeing of the living, too. For instance, restrictions\n\
    on savaging the dead protect those who loved them from the helpless hurt\n\
    of watching their memory and legacy tarnished.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But our obligations to the dead are stand-alone, too. Things we must do\n\
    because despite the loss of their bodies, the dead are still people,\n\
    too.</p>\n"
