  title: Stripped bare, Spitzer affair raises big question
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 17:55:36
  content_markup: "<p>The facts are simple. Elliot Spitzer, who fought organised crime and\n\
    corruption on Wall Street, resigned last week as New York\xE2\x80\x99s Governor\n\
    after Federal wiretaps caught him arranging to meet an out-of-town\n\
    hooker in his DC hotel.</p>\n\n\
    <p>It was the Mann Act of 1910 that brought Spitzer down. In its current\n\
    incarnation &ndash; the US Congress amended it in 1978 and again in 1986 &ndash; the\n\
    statute prohibits the transportation of people across state lines for\n\
    the purpose of prostitution.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Out of a job, his chance at a future run at the Presidency dashed, and\n\
    facing 20 years jail if convicted, you have to ask: what was the man\n\
    thinking? I\xE2\x80\x99m not sure, though one thing he did make clear during the\n\
    press conferences clocking his demise was that the answer was none of\n\
    our business. His behaviour was a \xE2\x80\x9Cprivate matter,\xE2\x80\x9D and his \xE2\x80\x9Cfailings\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    were private, too.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I couldn\xE2\x80\x99t agree more. If Spitzer says &ndash; which he does &ndash; that he failed\n\
    his Harvard-trained attorney wife Silda, his children and his entire\n\
    family by sleeping with a prostitute, who am I to disagree? But I once\n\
    lived and worked in New York and if I still did, I wouldn\xE2\x80\x99t think for a\n\
    moment that he had failed me.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I would feel the same about an Australian politician in Spitzer\xE2\x80\x99s shoes,\n\
    though in New South Wales and Victoria it would be unlikely that such an\n\
    official would ever be charged. Indoor commercial sex was decriminalised\n\
    n NSW, and partially legalised in Victoria, years ago. Among the reasons\n\
    why is the distaste small-l liberals feel for the state sticking its\n\
    beak into people\xE2\x80\x99s private affairs. What two consenting adults get up to\n\
    in bed is no one\xE2\x80\x99s business but their own.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Those on board &ndash; or should I say in bed? &ndash; with this philosophy may feel\n\
    that Spitzer\xE2\x80\x99s exit from public life is a shame, given all he had given\n\
    to it. So he had sex with a prostitute. How exactly does this impact on\n\
    his ability to do his job?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Americans may be wondering about this, too. Throughout the semen stains,\n\
    cigar speculations and impeachment proceedings that constituted the\n\
    Lewinsky affair, roughly 75% told pollsters they thought Bill Clinton\n\
    was fit to govern, and should remain as President.</p>\n\n\
    <p>But isn\xE2\x80\x99t it wrong for those meant to uphold the law to break it?\n\
    Absolutely. Doesn\xE2\x80\x99t Spitzer\xE2\x80\x99s behaviour show a failure of judgment or an\n\
    arrogant belief that he wouldn\xE2\x80\x99t be caught? Yep. Doesn\xE2\x80\x99t his zealous\n\
    pursuit of those running brothels &ndash; in the US and abroad &ndash; make him a\n\
    hypocrite? Possibly, though he only prosecuted operators, never \xE2\x80\x9Cjohns.\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    What about Spitzer\xE2\x80\x99s repeated use of the name of a friend and donor &ndash;\n\
    George Fox &ndash; to book the hotel room? Ai Carumba! With friends like that,\n\
    who needs enemies?</p>\n\n\
    <p>But to assertions that Spitzer\xE2\x80\x99s behaviour goes to character, I need to\n\
    ask, whose? In Australia, 19% of men have paid for sex at some point,\n\
    with reasons and situations varying. To my mind, it\xE2\x80\x99s those who cast\n\
    aspersions on all these men\xE2\x80\x99s\xE2\x80\x99 characters without knowing a thing abut\n\
    them or their situation &ndash; some cancer-stricken wives give their husbands\n\
    their blessing &ndash; who have character questions to answer.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Spitzer broke the law and for this he will rightly be made to pay. But\n\
    his story reminds us why laws that make commercial sex behind closed\n\
    doors between consenting adults a crime really need to change.</p>\n"
