    When the credits rolled I found myself pondering, tissue-box in lap, why\r\n\
    the Merry Makes tale is so inspiring. While articulate about all other\r\n\
    aspects of the troupe, neither Lucinda nor Janet could explain why-in\r\n\
    Janet\xE2\x80\x99s words-a Merry Makers\xE2\x80\x99 performance \xE2\x80\x9Cjust generates love and joy\r\n\
    and happiness, and no one wants to go home.\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    \r\n\
    I think I know. Firstly, is because the Merry Makers replace disgrace\r\n\
    with pride. The film is unflinching in its exploration of the shame\r\n\
    parents feel, or are made to feel by others, when a disabled child-one\r\n\
    with Down\xE2\x80\x99s syndrome or Fragile X or cerebral palsy-is born. \xE2\x80\x9CI felt\r\n\
    sick. My legs went to jelly. This can\xE2\x80\x99t be happening to me, she\xE2\x80\x99s too\r\n\
    beautiful,\xE2\x80\x9D recalls one mother. Another was told by her grandfather, as\r\n\
    the rest of her assembled family silently examined the new arrival,\r\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cnothing like this ever happened in our family.\xE2\x80\x9D\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But the Merry Makers is about celebrating ability, not disability. In\r\n\
    doing so, it allows the parents of special children to experience what\r\n\
    the rest of us take for granted: set-piece moments where we are\r\n\
    permitted to glory and gloat in our children\xE2\x80\x99s accomplishments, and\r\n\
    accept the admiration of others for what they have achieved.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The climax of The Music in Me is the Merry Makers\xE2\x80\x99 2005 performance in\r\n\
    the Sydney Entertainment Centre alongside Marcia Hines, Todd McKenney\r\n\
    and John Paul Young.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    When the Merry Makers take their bows to rapturous applause, you get the\r\n\
    feeling that this may be the first time in these people\xE2\x80\x99s lives where\r\n\
    they are the object of honest admiration and praise. When the camera\r\n\
    follows Merry Makers into the audience where they are hugged and\r\n\
    congratulated by ecstatic family members, you wonder if this is the\r\n\
    first time these parents have been given permission to publicly revel in\r\n\
    their child\xE2\x80\x99s accomplishments.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    A Merry Makers performance offers something unique to audiences, too. We\r\n\
    live in a world designed to make people with disabilities and those who\r\n\
    care for them invisible. When we do see the disabled and their carers,\r\n\
    it is usually because something is wrong. Disabled people abused in\r\n\
    specialized accommodation or carers who lack respite care or are having\r\n\
    their allowances slashed.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This near-exclusive representation of the disabled in the wider\r\n\
    community as those in plight, deserving our pity and rescue (and, in the\r\n\
    event we fail to provide either, our guilt) put paid to the \xE2\x80\x9Clove, joy\r\n\
    and happiness\xE2\x80\x9D offered by the Merry-Makers.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Feel good, do good. It works for the Merry Makers and, so it seems for\r\n\
    us, too."
