--- !ruby/object:CanpubArticle 
assets: 
attributes: 
  created_on: 2011-03-23 12:12:13
  slug: whose-time-is-it-anyway-peter
  site_id: "27"
  title: Whose Time is it Anyway, Peter?
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 18:00:40
  content_markup: "<p>Peter Bloody Costello. Thank heavens the man is about to exit the\n\
    national political stage because, quite frankly, I\xE2\x80\x99m not sure I could\n\
    take another minute of him.</p>\n\n\
    <p>It\xE2\x80\x99s not the smirk. My problem is the sense of entitlement. The standard\n\
    analysis of Costello\xE2\x80\x99s failure to challenge Howard for the leadership is\n\
    that he lacked the courage. Peter Costello, said Paul Keating back in\n\
    2005, has the heart the size of a caraway seed. This is probably true,\n\
    but certainly too superficial. Listening to Costello blather on to those\n\
    who care about the whys and wherefores of the challenge-that-never-was,\n\
    what I hear is man who didn\xE2\x80\x99t think he should have to take risks or work\n\
    up a sweat in order to be appointed &ndash; forget about elected to &ndash; one of\n\
    the highest offices in the land. He seemed to feel others should simply\n\
    recognise his obvious qualifications for the post and hand it over, tied\n\
    with a bow.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Costello\xE2\x80\x99s post ministerial career reeks of the same sense of nobless\n\
    self-oblige. While writers around the nation wait tables or sell socks\n\
    or try and squeeze in few hours at the computer late at night after\n\
    their day job is done and the kids are asleep, he rakes in a\n\
    back-bencher\xE2\x80\x99s salary while unapologetically writing his memoirs. No\n\
    need for Peter to scrape about for a rare and piddling literature grant\n\
    that other writers would make Faustian deals to secure despite the fact\n\
    they barely cover the rent. He\xE2\x80\x99ll just let the people of Higgins cover\n\
    it. And if they don\xE2\x80\x99t like it? Well, off with their heads.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Apparently, this sort of tacit tax-payer literary retreat is the Member\n\
    for Higgins\xE2\x80\x99 due, given all he had \xE2\x80\x9Ccontributed\xE2\x80\x9D during this time of\n\
    office. Apparently he is entitled to stay in the seat of Higgins for as\n\
    long as he wants until plans for his future career moves have\n\
    solidified. Or so say key members of the Canberra Press gallery, who\n\
    continue to report &ndash; with no sign of concern or alarm &ndash; on the \xE2\x80\x9CSalary\n\
    Accepted but No One Home\xE2\x80\x9D sign that has been on the former Treasurer\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    office door for close to a year.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Well I\xE2\x80\x99m alarmed. Alarmed and aghast. I mean this is the man who, with\n\
    his now-nemesis John Howard, spoke in glowing terms about programs like\n\
    work for the dole because they reflected the \xE2\x80\x9Cbenefits of mutual\n\
    obligation.\xE2\x80\x9D This from a key point man in a government that routinely\n\
    disparaged those on welfare as \xE2\x80\x9Cdole bludgers,\xE2\x80\x9D and criticised\n\
    Australians who didn\xE2\x80\x99t move interstate to find work as \xE2\x80\x9Cjob snobs.\xE2\x80\x9D This\n\
    from a man who insisted the unemployed become more \xE2\x80\x9Cself-sufficient,\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    and that welfare benefits be understood as a \xE2\x80\x9Csocial support in a time\n\
    of need, not a permanent handout.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Costello isn\xE2\x80\x99t unemployed but if there was any justice in the world, he\n\
    would be. Out on his ass in a pile of snow streaked yellow with dog pee.\n\
    I\xE2\x80\x99ve worked in a number of places in my time, but none where I had the\n\
    option to throw aside the job description so I could use the office\n\
    space to focus on things I found more lucrative and interesting.</p>\n\n\
    <p>That a Federal MP gets away with cheating his electorate of a\n\
    representative more interested in improving their life stories than\n\
    telling his, while they foot the bill-a sort of job-bludging that if we\n\
    were in his shoes and he were still Treasurer he would surely have\n\
    condemned &ndash; shames us all.</p>\n"
