    <p>Where the rights of women seeking abortions are taken seriously (and\n\
    these include their right to follow the dictates of their conscience, to\n\
    informed decision making about their health, to timely medical care and\n\
    to life), the absolutist approach seems inadequate at best. At worst, it\n\
    seems to disregard the pregnant woman\xE2\x80\x99s basic humanity.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Perhaps this fact is why most of those arguing for a change to\n\
    Victoria\xE2\x80\x99s conscience clause rarely mention women by name. They don\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    directly say, \xE2\x80\x9Cwe don\xE2\x80\x99t care if women die, doctors conscience rights are\n\
    supreme\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Rather they condemn the new law\xE2\x80\x99s \xE2\x80\x9Ccoercion\xE2\x80\x9D of individual health\n\
    workers and healthcare organisations to act contrary to their\n\
    consciences by requiring \xE2\x80\x9Cparticipation in abortion through \xE2\x80\xA6 direct\n\
    assistance.\xE2\x80\x9D They declaim with high dugeon the \xE2\x80\x9Cextraordinary attempt by\n\
    pro-abortion legislators\xE2\x80\x9D to threaten the livelihoods health\n\
    practitioners who \xE2\x80\x9Care unwilling to \xE2\x80\xA6 perform an abortion,\xE2\x80\x9D but never\n\
    mention that the only compulsion to provide abortion in the Victorian\n\
    legislation is in an emergency where it is necessary to preserve a\n\
    woman\xE2\x80\x99s life.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The conscience clause in Victoria\xE2\x80\x99s new abortion law requires just two\n\
    things from doctor\xE2\x80\x99s wanting to be excused from what the Victorian Law\n\
    Reform Commission described as the \xE2\x80\x9Cgeneral expectation that\n\
    practitioners will provide medical services\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The first is that they don\xE2\x80\x99t exercise this freedom at the cost of a\n\
    woman\xE2\x80\x99s life. The second is that they ensure their refusal to provide\n\
    timely medical care doesn\xE2\x80\x99t translate into her inability to get timely\n\
    medical care by providing an effective referral.</p>\n\n\
    <p>For those willing to mention women by name, this seems the least they\n\
    can do. After all, women have rights, too.</p>\n"
