    Again the problem is equality. If parents of both genders use flexible\r\n\
    work conditions, then the associated costs will fall to both. But if\r\n\
    only mothers are demanding such arrangements, then they become the group\r\n\
    some employers would prefer to avoid hiring, or will choose to\r\n\
    marginalise on the aptly named \xE2\x80\x9Cmummy-track\xE2\x80\x9D, while fathers and\r\n\
    childless workers get away scot-free.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The Government\xE2\x80\x99s new employment standards are not just blind to\r\n\
    persistent inequalities of gender, but to social class as well. As Labor\r\n\
    knows, bearing and raising children is expensive. Add to this the\r\n\
    soaring cost of housing, and few Australians have the luxury of having\r\n\
    one parent not working for years at a time. Any government serious about\r\n\
    offering the bulk of Australian parents real opportunities to care for\r\n\
    their children would ensure that parental leave was paid.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Paid parental leave has been a political football for too long. Last\r\n\
    month the National Civic Council took Tony Abbott to task for supporting\r\n\
    maternity (not parental) leave, which it sees as part of a feminist\r\n\
    conspiracy \xE2\x80\x9Cto reward women who make feminist-approved lifestyle\r\n\
    choices\xE2\x80\x9D. Conservative Christians are able to influence Labor as well -\r\n\
    the party dropped its commitment to paid maternity leave from its\r\n\
    platform before the last election, then flipped the issue to the\r\n\
    neo-liberal Productivity Commission to rule on when it won the election.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    We need to set the squealing of minorities aside and put the financial,\r\n\
    social and emotional needs of the majority of Australian mothers,\r\n\
    fathers and children first.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Australian mums and dads need, want and have a right to employment and\r\n\
    to share the work of looking after their children. Work and care must be\r\n\
    shared and parental leave must be paid. It really is as simple as that."
