  title: Support for Dying Friend our Final Gift
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 18:10:28
  content_markup: "<p>A READER &ndash; a qualified scientist I\xE2\x80\x99ll call Ron &ndash; asks for my view on a\n\
    dilemma that pitted his personal and professional integrity, and belief\n\
    in absolute truths, against his love for a dying friend.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Ron\xE2\x80\x99s friend, also a scientist, was dying of cancer. \xE2\x80\x9CHe said that he\n\
    would never use magic bullets,\xE2\x80\x9D Ron says, \xE2\x80\x9Cbut after two years of great\n\
    pain he turned to \xE2\x80\xA6 a [medical] device I knew \xE2\x80\xA6 was a blatant scam.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Should Ron have been honest and told his friend what he thought about\n\
    his medical choices, or supported his friend in the choices he made,\n\
    whatever Ron thought of them? Ron chose to keep his mouth shut. His\n\
    friend died some months later. Now, he wonders, did he do the right\n\
    thing?</p>\n\n\
    <p>I think so. What really mattered in this situation was that Ron kept\n\
    faith with the requirements of being a friend, not with his beliefs\n\
    about the importance of medical interventions having a base in evidence.\n\
    His friend was terminally ill and the Western medical kit bag was\n\
    clearly empty so whatever he chose to do or not do was not likely to\n\
    substantially alter the final result.</p>\n\n\
    <p>People at the end stage of a terminal illness have two options. One is\n\
    to put their affairs in order and live their life to the fullest, in\n\
    full knowledge that death is imminent. The other is to fight, not\n\
    necessarily in the belief they can win, but to assert control by\n\
    resisting the unwanted end.</p>\n\n\
    <p>In Helen Garner\xE2\x80\x99s novel <em>The Spare Room</em>, the dying Nicola injects\n\
    massive doses of vitamin C, then tosses off the pain and noxious side\n\
    effects as evidence the intervention is \xE2\x80\x9Csavaging the tumours and\n\
    driving them out\xE2\x80\x9D. Nicola\xE2\x80\x99s friend, Helen, rails at Nicola\xE2\x80\x99s naivety.\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9CTheir treatments are bullshit, Nicola. They\xE2\x80\x99re ripping you off. They\n\
    can\xE2\x80\x99t cure cancer.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>But the truth is that what frightens and enrages Helen is not Nicola\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    non-evidence-based approach to medicine. It\xE2\x80\x99s her friend\xE2\x80\x99s refusal to\n\
    accept her own death. \xE2\x80\x9CYou\xE2\x80\x99re using that bloody clinic to distract\n\
    yourself,\xE2\x80\x9D Helen tells Nicola.\\\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9CDon\xE2\x80\x99t say it, Hel,\xE2\x80\x9D says Nicola. She raises one palm. \xE2\x80\x9CDon\xE2\x80\x99t tell me.\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    But Helen won\xE2\x80\x99t be stopped. \xE2\x80\x9CYou\xE2\x80\x99ve got to get ready.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>It is easier for those of us who love and care for the terminally ill to\n\
    witness their smooth transition through the Kubler-Ross stages of dying:\n\
    denial, anger, bargaining, depression and acceptance. We sleep better\n\
    knowing that as their time approached, our friend or family member was\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cready\xE2\x80\x9D and \xE2\x80\x9Cat peace\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The truth is that not everyone does dying the same way. Some will never\n\
    come to acceptance. They will \xE2\x80\x9Cgo on fighting right to their last\n\
    breath\xE2\x80\x9D, explains the nurse who comes to look after Nicola. \xE2\x80\x9CAnd it is\n\
    one way of doing it.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>For Helen, it was recognising that it was not the idiotic fruitlessness\n\
    of Nicola\xE2\x80\x99s vitamin C detox that was distressing and enraging her. It\n\
    was Nicola\xE2\x80\x99s inability to \xE2\x80\x9Cwork towards a glorious moment of\n\
    enlightenment\xE2\x80\x9D and to admit she was dying and, by so doing, allow Helen\n\
    and others who loved her to accept and be open about it, too.</p>\n\n\
    <p>However painful we find it, supporting our friends to die as they see\n\
    fit can be our final gift to them. Biting his tongue, as Ron did about\n\
    the sham nature of his friend\xE2\x80\x99s last-ditch medical efforts, didn\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    compromise Ron\xE2\x80\x99s integrity. It gave his friend permission to die\n\
    fighting and was the act of a true friend.</p>\n"
