    Discussed, designed and sold in the language of \xE2\x80\x9Cmums\xE2\x80\x9D, they flagrantly\r\n\
    disregard the role men should - and many want to - play in the lives of\r\n\
    their children. By failing to talk about childcare and paid leave as\r\n\
    something of critical importance to children, men and women, both\r\n\
    political parties doom us to more of the same work/life crunch. More\r\n\
    oppressed women, more dissatisfied men, more children with exhausted\r\n\
    mums and absent dads.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Did you know that Australian men - 68 per cent in one poll - want more\r\n\
    involvement in their children\xE2\x80\x99s lives, but are impeded by work demands?\r\n\
    Did you know that children whose fathers contribute meaningfully to\r\n\
    their care have improved social skills, higher self-esteem and better\r\n\
    results at school?\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Do you know that children tell researchers they want to spend more time\r\n\
    with their fathers, and no amount of additional mother-time quells that\r\n\
    ache? Did you know that women doing most of the second-shift of\r\n\
    childcare and housework report feeling guilty and exhausted? Those who\r\n\
    work part-time or stay at home reduce their lifetime earnings by at\r\n\
    least $160,000 per child, end up on the \xE2\x80\x9Cmummy track\xE2\x80\x9D when they return\r\n\
    to work and wind up with 50 per cent less superannuation than men on\r\n\
    similar wages.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The most obvious solution to this problem continues to be overlooked -\r\n\
    namely, that fathers and mothers share fairly the joys and burdens of\r\n\
    paid employment and caring for their children - speaks volumes about the\r\n\
    capacity of vested interests and entrenched social attitudes to stifle\r\n\
    progress.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    That this is the case seems particularly clear given the ease with which\r\n\
    a gender-equity paradigm could be given effect in policy. All we need to\r\n\
    do is this: we need to say \xE2\x80\x9Cparental leave\xE2\x80\x9D and mean it. We need to\r\n\
    follow the lead of comparable OECD countries by allocating paid parental\r\n\
    leave entitlements to families in a way that allows them to share it,\r\n\
    and with a use-it-or-lose-it component for dads.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Male leave must be actively encouraged in the short term because of our\r\n\
    stubborn insistence on defining childcare and paid leave as \xE2\x80\x9Cwoman\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    issues\xE2\x80\x9D. This has meant that despite many men wanting to care for their\r\n\
    infants (50 per cent in one British study), they fear being ridiculed\r\n\
    and punished as \xE2\x80\x9Cunserious\xE2\x80\x9D if they do.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Use-it-or-lose-it provisions allow men to care for their children\r\n\
    without suffering workplace repercussions, while leaving those who don\xE2\x80\x99t\r\n\
    free to knock back their entitlement.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    At the start of the 21st century, the shift to a gender equity paradigm\r\n\
    - and to serious, costed policy to match - is long overdue.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    It is time for a paid leave policy that includes fathers as equal\r\n\
    participants, and promotes the best interests of children. It is time to\r\n\
    put an end to all the waste, not just of female talent, but of the work\r\n\
    of past generations of feminists who raised their sons to share the\r\n\
    earning and the caring with their partners - until backward-looking\r\n\
    policy and rhetoric made them think again.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Repeat after me: the key to female liberation is men."
