  title: Fighting for Virile Values - This is Tony Abbott
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 18:09:53
  content_markup: "<p>Tony Abbott is said to be likeable. I believe it, though I\xE2\x80\x99ve only met\n\
    him once. Introduced by a <em>Crikey!</em> journalist in Parliament House\n\
    Canberra, where I had gone to advocate against Abbott\xE2\x80\x99s continued\n\
    ministerial control over the fertility control drug RU486, the Health\n\
    Minister refused to shake my hand.</p>\n\n\
    <p>It was an honest move from an un-stage-managed man, and I didn\xE2\x80\x99t have a\n\
    problem with it. He didn\xE2\x80\x99t like me and he let it show. It was as\n\
    straight and simple as that.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The Opposition leader\xE2\x80\x99s recent attacks on the Prime Minister\xE2\x80\x99s character\n\
    are designed to highlight this virtue. By accusing Kevin Rudd of\n\
    waffle-speak, standing for nothing and \xE2\x80\x9Cgutless[ing] out,\xE2\x80\x9D Abbott\n\
    invites us to brand him in contrasting terms: as a straight-talking\n\
    leader with strong views and values, and a willingness to defend them.</p>\n\n\
    <p>All fine and good, though it does beg the question-what does Abbott\n\
    believe in? As Prime Minister, what policies would we expect him to\n\
    design, and to fight to implement?</p>\n\n\
    <p>Abbott\xE2\x80\x99s background, employment history and associations offer some\n\
    clues. Born in 1957, he was schooled at (Jesuit) St Ignatius College\n\
    before studying for the Priesthood. He subsequently worked as a\n\
    journalist and political press secretary before leading the successful\n\
    campaign against an Australian republic. He is associated with groups\n\
    that favour censorship but are opposed to legal abortion, dying with\n\
    dignity, stem-cell research and gay rights. These include the National\n\
    Civic Council, the Lyons Forum, the Endeavour Forum and the Australian\n\
    Christian Lobby.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Abbott recently described Aboriginal welcome to country ceremonies as a\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cgenuflection to political correctness\xE2\x80\x9D and \xE2\x80\x9Cout-of-place tokenism.\xE2\x80\x9D\n\
    However, he believes Federal Parliament should continue to start the day\n\
    with the Lord\xE2\x80\x99s Prayer.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Abbott believes the \xE2\x80\x9Cargument [on climate change] is absolute crap\xE2\x80\x9D. So\n\
    far, he has rejected all proven and economically orthodox means of\n\
    pricing carbon.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Abbott told <em>60 Minutes</em> in what he later described as a \xE2\x80\x9Cspontaneous\n\
    answer\xE2\x80\x9D that homosexuality makes him feel \xE2\x80\x9Ca bit threatened.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Health Minister Abbott\xE2\x80\x99s statements and policies on abortion renewed\n\
    national debate about the issue. He described \xE2\x80\x9Cthe fact that 100,000\n\
    [Australian] women choose to end their pregnancies\xE2\x80\x9D as a \xE2\x80\x9Cnational\n\
    tragedy\xE2\x80\x9D that left a \xE2\x80\x9Clegacy of unutterable shame.\xE2\x80\x9D He said there was \xE2\x80\x9Ca\n\
    bizarre double standard\xE2\x80\xA6where someone who kills a pregnant woman\xE2\x80\x99s baby\n\
    is guilty of murder but a woman who aborts an unborn baby is simply\n\
    exercising choice.\xE2\x80\x9D The figure of 100,000 turned out to be wrong.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Abbott voted against legislation allowing Australian scientists to do\n\
    research using embryonic stem cells.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Abbott wants to return to at fault-divorce, supporting legislation that\n\
    would require spouses to prove offences like adultery, habitual\n\
    drunkenness or cruelty before they can separate.</p>\n\n\
    <p>At the launch of a collection of B.A. Santamaria\xE2\x80\x99s letters, Abbott\n\
    lauded his mentor for the view that \xE2\x80\x9Cit [is] impossible to be a passive\n\
    Christian.\xE2\x80\x9D Abbott argued that the Howard government\xE2\x80\x99s decisions to\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Coverturn the Northern Territory\xE2\x80\x99s euthanasia law, ban gay marriage,\n\
    stop the ACT heroin trial, provide additional financial support for\n\
    one-income families, and try to reduce abortion numbers through\n\
    pregnancy support counseling\xE2\x80\x9D showed that the \xE2\x80\x9Ceight Catholics\xE2\x80\xA6in\n\
    the\xE2\x80\xA6Cabinet\xE2\x80\x9D had turned the \xE2\x80\x9Ctide of secular humanism.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Despite this, he recently implied on ABC\xE2\x80\x99s <em>Q&amp;A</em> that public and media\n\
    interest in his Catholic beliefs was unfair.</p>\n\n\
    <p>This is who Tony Abbott is and what he believes. It\xE2\x80\x99s up to us to decide\n\
    whether we want this sort of man, fighting for this sort of Australia,\n\
    to be the next PM.</p>\n"
