  content: "Craig Venter is back in the news. The entrepreneurial geneticist\r\n\
    recently announced he has created a new form of synthetic life. The new\r\n\
    microbe, which thrives and replicates with only a man-made genome, paves\r\n\
    the way for a world full of organisms that are built to order rather\r\n\
    than evolved.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The technique, reported in the peer-reviewed journal *Science*, required\r\n\
    20 scientists, ten years and $USD40 million to develop. ExxonMobil,\r\n\
    however, has already placed an order with the J Craig Venter Institute\r\n\
    for an algae that can convert carbon dioxide from the atmosphere into\r\n\
    fuel, taking estimates of value into the trillions.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    So far, concerns about the development by ethicists and religionists\r\n\
    have been predictable, and largely miss the point. Yes, there are risks\r\n\
    the organism could jump the lab, but Venter has inserted what he says\r\n\
    are fail-safe mechanisms into the microbe to render it harmless in the\r\n\
    outside world. All scientific inquiry entails some risk. The question is\r\n\
    whether those risks can be managed and are worth taking given the\r\n\
    possible benefits.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    It is also true that Venter\xE2\x80\x99s contribution allows humans to play God,\r\n\
    but surely this is what humans have long sought to do. How else can we\r\n\
    understand humankind\xE2\x80\x99s attempts to predict earthquakes or vaccinate\r\n\
    against diseases than a spirited attempt to control and influence the\r\n\
    vagaries of the natural - or God given - world?\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The real problems posed by the Venter development are the stale legal\r\n\
    and policy frameworks governing the world into which it\xE2\x80\x99s been birthed.\r\n\
    Venter makes much of the \xE2\x80\x9Csocietal good\xE2\x80\x9D he believes will come of what\r\n\
    he describes as \xE2\x80\x9Cone of the most powerful technologies and industrial\r\n\
    drivers\xE2\x80\x9D. He says he is concerned that the applications of his work are\r\n\
    used \xE2\x80\x9Cfor the benefit of all\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Maybe. But in a world where key features of modern day patent law date\r\n\
    back to the 1600\xE2\x80\x99s, and permit individuals or corporations to lock up\r\n\
    scientific knowledge as a source of private profit, consideration of the\r\n\
    public good remains optional.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Ventor\xE2\x80\x99s history suggests a keen interest in making knowledge critical\r\n\
    to public health private intellectual property. His man-made microbe\r\n\
    contains watermarks, five amino acid codes, that include quotations, an\r\n\
    email address and the names of people involved in the \xC2\xA330million project\r\n\
    (Dr Frankenstein not included).\r\n\
    \r\n\
    In the 1990s, his former company Celera Genomics raced against a\r\n\
    publicly funded project to sequence the human genome. At the time, he\r\n\
    had already applied to control the intellectual rights on more than 300\r\n\
    genes.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Luckily, he lost. In 2000 then-US President Clinton and British Prime\r\n\
    Minister Tony Blair jointly announced that an international consortium\r\n\
    working cooperatively and funded by public monies had produced a rough\r\n\
    draft of the genome, which a White House press release said would \xE2\x80\x9Clead\r\n\
    to new ways to prevent, diagnose, treat and cure disease\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But we may not be so lucky next time, and this is the point. New areas\r\n\
    of science like genomics have long been outpacing the laws and policies\r\n\
    that seek to govern them. Legislators and regulators urgently need to\r\n\
    catch up.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Our view is that where existing research and intellectual property\r\n\
    frameworks are adequate to ensure that the building blocks of life -\r\n\
    whether evolved or created-remain in public hands, well and good.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But where such frameworks tilt towards handing any individual or\r\n\
    corporation sole ownership of knowledge, knowledge that belongs to and\r\n\
    can be used to benefit all of us, we have a problem. A problem most\r\n\
    recently seen in the shut down of research critical to discovering the\r\n\
    cures for diseases like autism, brain cancer and neurological disease by\r\n\
    StemCells Inc on the grounds that the researcher was using a technique\r\n\
    he had helped develop but they had patented.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Patents over genes, the building blocks of life or what Venter calls\r\n\
    \xE2\x80\x98DNA computer code,\xE2\x80\x99 are wrong. They are wrong in moral and in practical\r\n\
    terms. They are wrong because they allow individuals or corporations to\r\n\
    exclusively control information that belongs to all of us, and wrong\r\n\
    because their patents discourage scientific progress or reserve its\r\n\
    benefits to those who can pay.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This view is shared by Nobel prize winners Joseph Stiglitz and John\r\n\
    Sulston, who recently argued in *The Wall Street Journal* that gene\r\n\
    patents, \xE2\x80\x9Cnot only prevent the use of knowledge in ways that would most\r\n\
    benefit society, they may even impede scientific progress. Every\r\n\
    scientific advance is built on those that came before it. There is still\r\n\
    a great deal to learn about our genes, particularly how they contribute\r\n\
    to disease. Gene patents inhibit access to the most basic information\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Venter\xE2\x80\x99s synthetic life form only adds weight to the passionate claims\r\n\
    from medical associations, geneticists, patients and academics have been\r\n\
    making for years that the patenting of human genes is unproductive and\r\n\
    unfair and must be stopped.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Next month a long-awaited report from the Australian Senate into the\r\n\
    impact of the granting of patents over human and microbial genes will be\r\n\
    handed down. Australian lawmakers must not miss this critical\r\n\
    opportunity to ensure that this country\xE2\x80\x99s regulatory framework places\r\n\
    the health and wellbeing of the Australian people and Australian\r\n\
    environment above private profit.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Scientific knowledge of evolved and created life must remain in public\r\n\
    hands.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    By Leslie Cannold and Luigi Palombi\r\n\
    \r\n\
    *Professor Luigi Palombi is Director of the Genetic Sequence Right\r\n\
    Project at the Australian National University and author of Gene\r\n\
    Cartels.*"
