  content_markup: "<p><em>It\xE2\x80\x99s easy taking candy from a baby. That doesn\xE2\x80\x99t make it right.</em></p>\n\n\
    <p>This is James, a NSW scripture teacher: \xE2\x80\x9CThe great opportunity we have\n\
    in teaching scripture in our primary schools \xE2\x80\xA6 is that we\xE2\x80\x99re allowed to\n\
    teach it up to an hour a week \xE2\x80\xA6 I spoke to a \xE2\x80\xA6 student \xE2\x80\xA6 and I said:\n\
    \xE2\x80\x98Did you know that God loves you?\xE2\x80\x99 and he said: \xE2\x80\x98No I didn\xE2\x80\x99t.\xE2\x80\x99 Then I\n\
    went through John 3:16 and asked him if he\xE2\x80\x98d ever heard that before and\n\
    he said \xE2\x80\x99No.\xE2\x80\x99 And it shocked me [that] \xE2\x80\xA6 this boy didn\xE2\x80\x99t even know that\n\
    his creator loved him and cared about him \xE2\x80\xA6 and sent him the Lord Jesus.\n\
    The challenge is before us to capture the hearts and minds of children\n\
    and youth, to talk about Jesus in the scripture classes \xE2\x80\xA6\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>This is Janet. She works for YouthWorks. Here\xE2\x80\x99s how she advised her\n\
    fellow scripture teachers to defend against the \xE2\x80\x9Cthreat\xE2\x80\x9D posed by ethics\n\
    classes being available to primary kids whose parents opt them out of\n\
    religious education:</p>\n\n\
    <p>\xE2\x80\x9CIn the younger years we need to sow the seeds strongly of the gospel\n\
    and scripture. Get the Bible into people\xE2\x80\x99s homes or parts of the Bible \xE2\x80\xA6\n\
    Get scripture into people\xE2\x80\x99s homes, so that by the time [kids] are in\n\
    year 6 they\xE2\x80\x99ve had a strong grounding in what the gospel is all about\n\
    and they won\xE2\x80\x99t be so easily falling for the ethics material.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>This is Health Minister Nicola Roxon, who earlier this year rejected the\n\
    findings of the government\xE2\x80\x99s own preventive health taskforce to regulate\n\
    the volume and types of advertising directed at young children.\\\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9CWhile the government is supportive of limiting the exposure of children\n\
    to advertising that may unduly influence them, the government will not\n\
    consider regulatory action at this time.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Adults are confused. Confused not so much as to the special\n\
    vulnerability of young children to adult attempts to influence them (my\n\
    reading of the above quotes suggest they understand this very well), but\n\
    confused as to what this vulnerability demands of the grown-ups who are\n\
    in a position to influence children, particularly if they hold positions\n\
    of authority.</p>\n\n\
    <p>If only influence-peddlers would self-regulate. If only they were the\n\
    sort of people who, however much they stood to gain financially or\n\
    however worthy they thought their message, would never take advantage of\n\
    a child\xE2\x80\x99s innocence to clinch a sale.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Don\xE2\x80\x99t hold your breath. YouthWorks\xE2\x80\x99 advice to religious education\n\
    teachers to hit six-year-olds hard to defend against later parental\n\
    decisions to opt their kids out of religious education is risible.\n\
    Australian industry is no better, with self-regulation having led to\n\
    nothing more than a marked increase in food marketing to kids.\\\n\
    Parents are often lambasted for not shielding their offspring from such\n\
    unfair influence but children\xE2\x80\x99s ads come via the net, TV, Facebook,\n\
    email and mobile phones. Without umbilical attachment, no parent can\n\
    defend against this, which may be why 91 per cent of consumers in a 2008\n\
    survey supported stronger government action.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Children are easily misled. They lack the cognitive skills and abilities\n\
    to \xE2\x80\x9Cread\xE2\x80\x9D persuasive messages, whether these come at them in the\n\
    classroom, or via a screen. From ages six to seven, kids think ads offer\n\
    information, while those aged seven to eight can\xE2\x80\x99t discern the\n\
    difference between information and the intent of an ad to persuade. By\n\
    ages 10 to 12, most kids are still unable to identify the sales\n\
    techniques being used to get them to say, \xE2\x80\x9Cyes\xE2\x80\x9D.</p>\n\n\
    <p>That we know this and don\xE2\x80\x99t stop the influence-peddlers taking candy\n\
    from our babies should shame us all.</p>\n"
