  title: What the First Female PM Means for Australian Women
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 18:11:48
  content_markup: "<p><em>What does Australia\xE2\x80\x99s first female PM mean for Australian women?\n\
    Nothing. And Everything.</em></p>\n\n\
    <p>In the tense hours between 7pm on Wednesday until Labor\xE2\x80\x99s caucus meeting\n\
    on Thursday morning, women were emoting on Twitter: \xE2\x80\x9CMy little boys may\n\
    wake up to a female prime minister. I could burst into tears.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>When Julia Gillard emerged as the nation\xE2\x80\x99s new leader, we had this:\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9CDaughters of Australia: ring your mum and say thank you for the\n\
    possibility of Julia.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>What does it really mean to have a female prime minister? What will\n\
    change for Australian women, men and the country as a whole. Nothing.\n\
    And everything.\\\n\
    Nothing because women in power are no different to men. As Julia Baird\n\
    wrote in her book on the subject, Australia\xE2\x80\x99s female politicians\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cbackstab .., pursue \xE2\x80\xA6 personal ambitions and openly criticise \xE2\x80\xA6 each\n\
    other\xE2\x80\x9D in the same manner as men.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Despite this, the anointing of a female prime minister &ndash; by a female\n\
    governor-general no less &ndash; does have the power to rock our world.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The paltry representation, or absence, of women in roles that are\n\
    visible, valued and influential has a cancerous effect on female\n\
    self-esteem. Young girls can\xE2\x80\x99t see it, so they don\xE2\x80\x99t dream it. Women,\n\
    who understand that there can only be two reasons for their invisibility\n\
    &ndash; female inferiority of pervasive gender discrimination &ndash; feel angry or\n\
    depressed.</p>\n\n\
    <p>By proving wrong those who said there would not be a female prime\n\
    minister in our lifetimes, the likes of Gillard kindle hope and incite\n\
    rebellion. Less than an hour after Gillard was sworn in, female\n\
    journalists began tweeting about the absence of women in senior\n\
    editorial positions. Overheard in the newsroom: \xE2\x80\x9CYes, but where are the\n\
    female newspaper editors?\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Gillard may also have particular interest, empathy and insight into\n\
    gender-based discrimination. Certainly, she has experienced sexism. As a\n\
    student at Unley High she protested demands that girls stay after class\n\
    to tidy up while the boys had a good time. \xE2\x80\x9CAre you into women\xE2\x80\x99s\n\
    liberation, Julia?\xE2\x80\x9D the teacher asked, to which Gillard replied\n\
    scornfully, \xE2\x80\x9CI don\xE2\x80\x99t need women\xE2\x80\x99s liberation, I was born free.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>My favourite aspect of Gillard\xE2\x80\x99s ascendancy is how she made her move.\n\
    Characterisations of the process as one in which she had to be dragged\n\
    to the podium, or tapped by faction leaders to consider a challenge, are\n\
    mistaken. Gillard made her own assessment of the terminal nature of\n\
    Rudd\xE2\x80\x99s leadership and began summoning key MPs on Wednesday afternoon to\n\
    gauge support.</p>\n\n\
    <p>This may be Gillard\xE2\x80\x99s greatest gift to Australian women: the forthright\n\
    way she goes about her business as a powerful person in her own right.\n\
    By doing this, she normalises women in power not as women but as people,\n\
    with all the quirks and complexities of men. This makes her one of us\n\
    and her path one we might stride, too.</p>\n"
