    As the capacity of WikiLeaks to dictate and dominate the news cycle\r\n\
    grows, it has also become the story. Much of the chatter is from\r\n\
    journalists, who have traditionally seen it as a competitor and worried\r\n\
    that its commando-style, volunteer-dependent approach might be the\r\n\
    future of investigative reporting.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Such fears were ameliorated by the handling of the Afghan war documents:\r\n\
    WikiLeaks gave three news organisations early access to the documents,\r\n\
    which released them alongside their own coverage and analysis. News\r\n\
    chiefs saw this approach as an affirmation of the sifting, annotating\r\n\
    and interpreting skills of the \xE2\x80\x9Cprofessional journalist\xE2\x80\x9D. But amid the\r\n\
    backslapping, key moral questions about the WikiLeaks phenomenon have\r\n\
    been overlooked.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    The group believes transparency brings accountability and secrecy causes\r\n\
    corruption. Societies in search of honest institutions and a properly\r\n\
    functioning democracy require that powerful governments and corporations\r\n\
    put everything on the public record for citizens to analyse and make up\r\n\
    their minds. Where they fail in this responsibility, people of\r\n\
    conscience must act with organisations such as WikiLeaks to get the\r\n\
    truth out.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    There is much that is sound in this plan. It is true corruption relies\r\n\
    on secrecy and secrecy veils and nurtures corruption. It is correct to\r\n\
    say democracy is imperilled when institutions ritually rely on \xE2\x80\x9Cnational\r\n\
    security\xE2\x80\x9D and \xE2\x80\x9Ccommercial in confidence\xE2\x80\x9D to withhold information\r\n\
    required to ensure corporate or government integrity.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    WikiLeaks also issues challenges to the culture of secrecy itself. The\r\n\
    ease and security WikiLeaks provides to leakers and the minimalist\r\n\
    nature of the site\xE2\x80\x99s editorial control encourages leaking. The more\r\n\
    leaking there is, the greater the recognition among the powerful that no\r\n\
    secret is safe. One sane response to this new reality is for\r\n\
    institutions to abandon secrecy as their default mode and operate\r\n\
    transparently instead.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This is a citizen\xE2\x80\x99s world, one ruled - with a light touch - by\r\n\
    organisations such as WikiLeaks, but there will be problems. One obvious\r\n\
    one is that occasionally there are legitimate reasons for secrecy and\r\n\
    privacy.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    It\xE2\x80\x99s no good to say that decisions about this data can be made\r\n\
    collectively. Once information is known, it cannot be unknown.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This leaves WikiLeaks to decide. With power comes responsibility and\r\n\
    mistakes have been made. Founder Assange says the organisation will\r\n\
    review its procedures and react, though the effect on the guiding\r\n\
    philosophy of Wikileaks remains to be seen.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Interesting times ahead."
