    when in \xE2\x80\x9Creal Julia\xE2\x80\x9D mode, anyway - she remains a lesser-known quantity.\r\n\
    Where she has distinguished herself, or been noted by others, it is most\r\n\
    often for matters of form, not substance. She seems smart and\r\n\
    articulate, yet we have little sense of what direction she\xE2\x80\x99ll steer the\r\n\
    country because we don\xE2\x80\x99t know the things that really matter to her -\r\n\
    what she\xE2\x80\x99ll fight for and never compromise on, no matter what.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Gillard rarely discusses the things she believes in. Because of this, we\r\n\
    tend to assume. We assume that because she has a working class\r\n\
    background and made education the centrepiece of her parliamentary\r\n\
    maiden speech that she favours a first class public education system.\r\n\
    Having bravely asserted her lack of faith in God, we assume she will\r\n\
    defend the barrier between church and state. Because she is Australia\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    first female PM, we think she\xE2\x80\x99ll stand and fight for the policies women\r\n\
    need to succeed.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    But we are often proved wrong. In her short time in the top job Gillard\r\n\
    has refused to alter the way government funds state and private schools\r\n\
    and has expanded the school Christian chaplaincy program by a third. She\r\n\
    opposes gay marriage and was the strongest opponent in Rudd\xE2\x80\x99s kitchen\r\n\
    cabinet of the miserly paid parental leave scheme Australian feminists\r\n\
    battled for decades to achieve.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    To make matters more confusing, when Gillard moves against what we\r\n\
    thought she\xE2\x80\x99d defend, she tends to laud her stance as proof of her\r\n\
    metal. The MySchools website is a textbook case, though what she expects\r\n\
    us to draw from it is anyone\xE2\x80\x99s guess. Does she view her willingness to\r\n\
    screw an expected adversary - in this case, the education union - as\r\n\
    proof of a practical even-handedness that she sees as the essence of her\r\n\
    character? Or is this dispassionate judicial-like persona, concerned\r\n\
    with formal process rather than substance, all she is willing to share\r\n\
    with us, preferring to keep private the aspects of her character that\r\n\
    would reveal her policy preferences and her heart.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Whatever is the case, the real problem is that Labor\xE2\x80\x99s tactics have\r\n\
    undermined any claim to evidence-based policy at every turn. Whether\r\n\
    it\xE2\x80\x99s setting aside the Henry Tax Review to placate West Australian\r\n\
    miners, or pre-empting its own assessment of the National School\r\n\
    Chaplaincy Program to expand it by a third or proposing a citizens\r\n\
    assembly to address the science of climate change, Labor has done little\r\n\
    more than hand out taxpayer funds to marginal electorates or interest\r\n\
    groups that scream the loudest throughout the campaign. And since week\r\n\
    three, when Gillard shook of the shackles of Labor\xE2\x80\x99s election\r\n\
    strategists, she has been in charge and doing it her way.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Having said this, Abbott also seems determined to undermine his own\r\n\
    strengths on the character front. Avoiding press forums that might see\r\n\
    him go off message, he looks at times to be visibly straining on his\r\n\
    lead. While his pounding of the \xE2\x80\x9Cno means no\xE2\x80\x9D mantra in response to\r\n\
    Gillard\xE2\x80\x99s request for a debate was widely lauded as a blunder, I suspect\r\n\
    it did him good. It affirmed that, despite the muzzling, he remains the\r\n\
    same man: oblivious to a feminist anti-rape slogan familiar to many\r\n\
    12-year-olds, and one sincere in his illogical assertion that men with\r\n\
    daughters can\xE2\x80\x99t be sexist.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    There is something dispiriting about watching people we call leaders try\r\n\
    to suppress their souls, or pretend they never had one in the first\r\n\
    place. This is particularly the case when there seems no reason to have\r\n\
    gone to such lengths. As respected social researcher Hugh Mackay has\r\n\
    explained, campaigns have little impact on the election results. History\r\n\
    shows that polls taken just before campaigns begin usually point to the\r\n\
    result.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This appears to be confirmed by the latest Neilson poll, which has Labor\r\n\
    ahead 53 to 47 on a two party preferred basis, figures almost identical\r\n\
    to the 52 to 48 split the same poll recorded a week before the election\r\n\
    was called."
