  title: Talking About Rape
  updated_on: 2011-03-24 18:12:40
  content_markup: "<p>It\xE2\x80\x99s the end of the footy season, so everyone\xE2\x80\x99s talking about rape. Or,\n\
    more specifically, about the young women who were so stupid as to put\n\
    themselves in a position where they\xE2\x80\x99d be raped, or be able to claim\n\
    later that they were.</p>\n\n\
    <p>TV presenter Kerri-Anne Kennerley laid the blame on the \xE2\x80\x9Cstrays\xE2\x80\x9D who\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Cthrow &hellip; themselves at sportspeople\xE2\x80\x9D. \xE2\x80\x9CWhat do [women] expect,\xE2\x80\x9D she\n\
    asked, \xE2\x80\x9Cwhen they are out at night?\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>Former AFL player Spida Everitt was also scathing about, \xE2\x80\x9CYet another .\n\
    . . girl making alleged allegations after she awoke with &hellip; an\n\
    alleged guilty conscience.\xE2\x80\x9D</p>\n\n\
    <p>I have been raped. Twice. The first time was my first time &ndash; I was 17 &ndash;\n\
    but I didn\xE2\x80\x99t think of it as rape. Not even when the nightmares began\n\
    and, following that, the depression.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I just thought I was a stupid girl who put myself in harm\xE2\x80\x99s way and got\n\
    what I deserved. Embarrassed at being so dumb, I told no one what\n\
    happened. It was only years later when I stubbed my toe and couldn\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    stop crying that my mother strong-armed me into seeing a psychologist\n\
    and the story came out.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The second time was when an old boyfriend got my half-asleep roommate to\n\
    let him into the house in the middle of the night. I was in my room and\n\
    woke having sex. Surely this was a clear-cut case of rape but, again, I\n\
    didn\xE2\x80\x99t see it that way. Because now I was 21 and understood that you\n\
    can\xE2\x80\x99t thread a moving needle and I\xE2\x80\x99d had sex with him before so what was\n\
    the big deal and if I hadn\xE2\x80\x99t wanted it why didn\xE2\x80\x99t I scream?</p>\n\n\
    <p>In fact, what I did &ndash; then and later &ndash; was pretend everything was fine.\n\
    I acted like what happened was exactly what I chose to happen. I was not\n\
    prepared to contemplate the alternative framing of events and its\n\
    emotional corollary &ndash; that I\xE2\x80\x99d been raped again and this meant that I\n\
    wasn\xE2\x80\x99t safe anywhere, not even in my own bed.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I don\xE2\x80\x99t want pity. Indeed, it\xE2\x80\x99s fear of being seen as a victim that has\n\
    led me to keep my personal story quiet thus far. I tell it now to try to\n\
    inject the complex reality of sexual assault &ndash; how it happens and how\n\
    those who experience it attempt to get their heads around it &ndash; into the\n\
    public discussions we have most years at this time on the subject.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I also want to point to the contribution gender stereotypes make to the\n\
    problem. Like young women today, I was sold a double message. The\n\
    explicit one was that I was strong, capable and free to do what I chose\n\
    with my life and body &ndash; sexually and otherwise &ndash; and not be judged for\n\
    it.</p>\n\n\
    <p>The subterranean one was that if I acted as if I was entitled to be both\n\
    free and safe, and someone did hurt or rape me, it was my own stupid,\n\
    sluttish fault.</p>\n\n\
    <p>These contradictory messages have co-existed quietly in my psyche just\n\
    as they do for some young women today until the Kennerleys and Everitts\n\
    of the world lay them bare.</p>\n\n\
    <p>I laid my own demons to rest long ago. One thing that helped was the\n\
    acknowledgment by one of the men that something bad had happened and it\n\
    wasn\xE2\x80\x99t my fault. This was several years later and we were at a party. He\n\
    found me alone on the balcony and said this: \xE2\x80\x9CWhat happened &hellip; that\n\
    night. I didn\xE2\x80\x99t realise then but I do now. It wasn\xE2\x80\x99t right. I shouldn\xE2\x80\x99t\n\
    have done it.\xE2\x80\x9D I forgave him right then and there.</p>\n\n\
    <p>So where to now? Has increasing social and sexual freedom been good for\n\
    young women, or bad? The truth is that this is the wrong question to\n\
    ask. Equality and freedom are chances that some women will use poorly\n\
    and others well. Certainly every young woman, like every young man, will\n\
    make mistakes and get hurt. This is what coming of age is all about. The\n\
    hope is that as time moves on, and a critical number of generations\n\
    accumulate wisdom they can pass to their kids, the relative balance of\n\
    those who use their freedom wisely will grow.</p>\n\n\
    <p>For thousands of years, humans have lived in societies built on the\n\
    exercise of superior male strength and the inevitability of female\n\
    pregnancy. Inflexible and gender-inequitable rules for emotional and\n\
    physical engagement between the sexes arose from these realities.</p>\n\n\
    <p>As societies governed by the rule of law and populated by women with\n\
    access to reliable contraception become the norm, new rules of\n\
    engagement for relations between the sexes &ndash; ones based on mutual\n\
    understanding, respect and consent &ndash; will flourish.</p>\n\n\
    <p>There is no doubt that young men are changing. Many see women as their\n\
    equals, are well across the concept of consent and &ndash; in response to the\n\
    more assertive sexuality of their female peers &ndash; are interrogating the\n\
    \xE2\x80\x9Creal men always want it\xE2\x80\x9D stereotype as a first step towards a \xE2\x80\x9Cno means\n\
    no\xE2\x80\x9D mantra of their own.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Similarly, we must recognise young women who report sexual assault as\n\
    canaries in the coalmine. It is they who are blazing the trail towards\n\
    the safe and equal world we want for our daughters and sons. This is\n\
    because, unlike me at that age, they don\xE2\x80\x99t have the words of Kennerley\n\
    or Everitt in their head.</p>\n\n\
    <p>Instead, they believe that, just like their male mates, they should be\n\
    free to party with abandon when their team wins the grand final. And be\n\
    safe while they do it.</p>\n"
