    Among the tittle-tattle is the view of a US embassy staffer that French\r\n\
    President Nicolas Sarkozy is \xE2\x80\x9Cthin-skinned\xE2\x80\x9D with an \xE2\x80\x9Cauthoritarian\r\n\
    personal style\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    News items still refer to WikiLeaks as a whistleblowing website but all\r\n\
    references to whistleblowing - the act of informing on an individual\xE2\x80\x99s\r\n\
    or institution\xE2\x80\x99s corrupt or illicit behaviour - seem to have been\r\n\
    removed from the site.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Instead we learn that the organisation\xE2\x80\x99s goal is simply \xE2\x80\x9Cto bring\r\n\
    important news and information to the public\xE2\x80\x9D through leaks.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    We are told that \xE2\x80\x9Cpublishing improves transparency, and this\r\n\
    transparency creates a better society for all people\xE2\x80\x9D and that WikiLeaks\r\n\
    brings \xE2\x80\x9Ctruth to the world without fear or favour\xE2\x80\x9D. In cringeworthy text\r\n\
    accompanying the embassy cables, the US government is reminded of the\r\n\
    lesson of George Washington, the country\xE2\x80\x99s first president, who \xE2\x80\x9Ccould\r\n\
    not tell a lie\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Media and governments aren\xE2\x80\x99t lying when they fail to fling into the\r\n\
    public domain every document they write, any more than you and I are\r\n\
    being dishonest when we fail to speak every thought aloud or decline to\r\n\
    repeat the confidences of close friends to a football stadium of people.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    There is a legitimate role for editorial judgment and a need to protect\r\n\
    individual privacy in media and corporate dealings, not to mention\r\n\
    sometimes a requirement for secrecy in military operations, intelligence\r\n\
    gathering and diplomatic negotiations. The arbiter for disclosure is the\r\n\
    public interest.\\\r\n\
    It is vital that WikiLeaks not become about leaking for leaking\xE2\x80\x99s sake.\r\n\
    It must not abandon its fight against corruption in defence of the\r\n\
    public interest to favour what the Federation of American Scientists\r\n\
    calls \xE2\x80\x9Can assault on secrecy\xE2\x80\x9D.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    Instead, WikiLeaks must ensure it continues to grab headlines with the\r\n\
    same stories that have won it awards from Amnesty and made its name.\r\n\
    These include images of the Baghdad air strike and documents about\r\n\
    extra- judicial killings and disappearances in Kenya.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    WikiLeaks is a game-changer, providing the raw data that can be used to\r\n\
    shine light into the dark corners of corrupt corporate and civil\r\n\
    institutions. It can be expected to change the way governments and\r\n\
    businesses operate. In the future, openness may be the default and\r\n\
    arguments made about why something should stay secret. This profound and\r\n\
    important paradigm shift is largely down to WikiLeaks.\r\n\
    \r\n\
    This is why I hope the organisation will move to protect is own legacy,\r\n\
    and the public support required for its continuing influence, by\r\n\
    sticking to the task of whistleblowing, not just divulging secrets\r\n\
    because they\xE2\x80\x99re interesting or because it can."
